{"type":"message","id":"3b626cf9","parentId":"5e36d10b","timestamp":"2026-04-11T06:26:31.745Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"ollama_call_deb94ab4-d3fd-47bd-8311-154301053db7","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"total 56\ndrwxrwxr-x  2 tiny4lurv tiny4lurv  4096 Apr 11 08:22 .\ndrwxr-xr-x 17 tiny4lurv tiny4lurv  4096 Apr 10 20:07 ..\n-rw-rw-r--  1 tiny4lurv tiny4lurv 13362 Apr 11 07:47 article-how-to-fire-an-independent-contractor.md\n-rw-rw-r--  1 tiny4lurv tiny4lurv 14796 Apr 11 08:23 article-independent-contractor-non-compete.md\n-rw-rw-r--  1 tiny4lurv tiny4lurv 14679 Apr 11 08:22 article-independent-contractor-non-compete_ORIGINAL.md"}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":0,"durationMs":15,"aggregated":"total 56\ndrwxrwxr-x  2 tiny4lurv tiny4lurv  4096 Apr 11 08:22 .\ndrwxr-xr-x 17 tiny4lurv tiny4lurv  4096 Apr 10 20:07 ..\n-rw-rw-r--  1 tiny4lurv tiny4lurv 13362 Apr 11 07:47 article-how-to-fire-an-independent-contractor.md\n-rw-rw-r--  1 tiny4lurv tiny4lurv 14796 Apr 11 08:23 article-independent-contractor-non-compete.md\n-rw-rw-r--  1 tiny4lurv tiny4lurv 14679 Apr 11 08:22 article-independent-contractor-non-compete_ORIGINAL.md","cwd":"/home/tiny4lurv/.openclaw/workspace"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1775888791736}}
{"type":"message","id":"a3a1bad2","parentId":"3b626cf9","timestamp":"2026-04-11T06:26:37.488Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"\n\n\nYes — the file updated at 08:23 (original was 14,679 bytes, now 14,796). You saved it. Let me read the new version now.\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"ollama_call_130a7304-4577-40b1-a8c1-5a8936bb9359","name":"read","arguments":{"limit":50,"path":"/home/tiny4lurv/.openclaw/workspace/abroadworks/article-independent-contractor-non-compete.md"}}],"stopReason":"toolUse","api":"ollama","provider":"ollama","model":"minimax-m2.7:cloud","usage":{"input":49085,"output":157,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":49242,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"timestamp":1775888797488}}
{"type":"message","id":"1ab87494","parentId":"a3a1bad2","timestamp":"2026-04-11T06:26:37.516Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"ollama_call_130a7304-4577-40b1-a8c1-5a8936bb9359","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"**Title:** Independent Contractor Non-Compete Agreements: What They Can and Cannot Do for Your Business\n\n**Meta Description:** Non-compete clauses for contractors sound like protection. They are not. Learn what these agreements actually restrict, why courts often ignore them, and what actually keeps your business safe.\n\n**Keywords:** independent contractor non-compete, contractor non-compete clause, non-compete for self-employed, business protection contractors, non-compete enforceability\n\n---\n\n# Independent Contractor Non-Compete Agreements: What They Can and Cannot Do for Your Business\n\nAn employee spent 8 months developing and building sales funnels and marketing material for a small business. The business started gaining edge in the local market. Unexpectedly, the employee resigned and reached out to competitors with email sequences, ad copy, and information about internal process in exchange for a lump sum. The original employer lost the ground they had gained in the market and subsequently regretted not learning about or enforcing a strict independent contractor non-compete clause that, perhaps, would have prevented this loss.\n\nThe belief that a non-compete clause protects a small business from this exact scenario is widespread, intuitive, and, surprisingly, mostly wrong. Most micro-business owners who add a non-compete to a contractor agreement do so because they want protection against the contractor taking knowledge, clients, or work product. The non-compete cannot provide that protection.\n\n---\n\n## What a Non-Compete Actually Does\n\nA non-compete clause is a restraint on where a person can work after the relationship ends. It does not prevent a contractor from taking information. It does not stop them from using your processes or copying your funnels. It only restricts whether they can perform similar services for similar clients within a geographic area and time window defined in the agreement. If the contractor never planning to work in that same market or timeframe, the clause has no practical effect on their behavior at all.\n\nMost standard non-compete agreements for independent contractors specify a duration, a geographic radius, and a list of restricted activities. These restrictions apply after the work is done, after the invoice is paid, after the relationship is over. The contractor can still think about what they learned. They can still talk about it. They can still use general knowledge and skills. They simply cannot go work for a direct competitor within the defined window. That is the entire scope of what the agreement controls.\n\n> ***\"A non-compete controls where a contractor works next. It says nothing about what they know, what they build, or what they share.\"***\n\nThe gap between what business owners believe a non-compete does and what it actually does is not a drafting problem. It is a structural problem. The contract cannot reach into the contractor's head. It cannot prevent thought, conversation, or analogizing. It can only draw legal boundaries around where the contractor physically performs similar labor. When the fear is \"they will take what they learned and use it against me,\" the non-compete does not address that fear at all.\n\n---\n\n## What Courts and States Have Decided\n\nIt may seem that ensuring the requirements are met and coupled with other agreements works. Courts have reached various conclusions on this question, and the landscape is far less favorable than most business owners assume. The Federal Trade Commission issued a rule in 2024 that signaled the direction of travel on worker non-competes, with the FTC describing most non-competes as unfair methods of competition. That rule faced legal challenges and its current status is uncertain. State legislatures have moved faster regardless. State legislatures have moved faster. Four states have voided non-compete agreements entirely for independent contractors: California, Minnesota, North Dakota, and Oklahoma. If your contractor lives or works in any of these states, the non-compete you drafted is not worth the paper it is printed on.\n\nBeyond the four states that ban them outright, several jurisdictions enforce non-competes only when the contractor meets specific income thresholds. Washington State requires the contractor to earn more than $317,147.09 annually from the business to sustain enforceability. Washington, D.C. sets the bar at $162,164. For a micro-business paying a contractor for a single project or a short engagement, these thresholds are not merely high, they are effectively unreachable. The non-compete may be technically valid but practically useless. Courts in these jurisdictions will simply refuse to enforce the clause if the contractor did not cross the income threshold.\n\n> ***\"Four states void non-compete clauses entirely. Others enforce them only above specific income thresholds that most micro-business contractors never meet.\"***\n\nThe enforceability question does not end with income floors. Courts also weigh whether the restriction is reasonable in scope, duration, and geographic reach. A non-compete that attempts to cover every adjacent industry for two years will often be narrowed by a judge or thrown out entirely. What the business owner believed was comprehensive protection often collapses to a narrow window of actual enforcement the moment a judge reads the document.\n\n---\n\n## The Control Contradiction\n\nThe instinct to tighten control over a contractor relationship is understandable. It is also the precise behavior that creates the misclassification risk. Courts and government agencies do not ask whether you called someone a contractor. They ask whether you treated them like one.\n\nThe distinction between an independent contractor and an employee is not a label. It is a pattern of control. When a business owner sets hours, dictates process, provides equipment, and supervises the method of work, the contractor begins to look like an employee in the eyes of the law. The Internal Revenue Service, the Department of Labor, and most state agencies use a multi-factor test that weighs behavioral control heavily. A non-compete clause layered onto a relationship that already exhibits employee-like control does not add protection. It adds evidence that the contractor was misclassified. The attempt to restrict where the contractor works after the fact draws attention to how closely the business controlled the contractor during the engagement.\n\nThe case Chavez-DeRemer v. Magic Jenn, decided in 2024, resulted in a $9 million judgment against a business that attempted to enforce non-compete restrictions while treating its workers as employees in all practical senses. The court found that the business had exercised the degree of control associated with employment while attempting to impose post-termination restrictions reserved for true independent contractors. The contradiction between control during the relationship and restrictions after the relationship sank the employer's position entirely. The lesson is not that the non-compete was poorly drafted. The lesson is that the attempt to enforce one exposed the misclassification.\n\n> ***\"Attempting to tightly control a contractor's work environment to make a non-compete enforceable risks creating the very misclassification that destroys the agreement's enforceability.\"***\n\n\n[52 more lines in file. Use offset=51 to continue.]"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1775888797508}}
{"type":"message","id":"f4fa40fb","parentId":"1ab87494","timestamp":"2026-04-11T06:26:53.797Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"\n\nGot it — I can see the changes now. Updating notes:\n\n**Changes spotted (intro paragraph):**\n\n1. `\"Unexpectedly,\"` added before resignation — controls the story's pacing, signals the twist before stating it\n2. `\"The original employer lost the ground they had gained in the market and subsequently regretted...\"` — replaces the flat causal claim with a more human, regret-driven sentence\n3. `\"independent contractor non-compete clause\"` — made explicit, no longer assumes the reader knows what type of clause we're discussing\n4. `\"perhaps, would have\"` — hedge confirmed, per your earlier explanation\n\nThe word \"belief\" variation issue — I see the second paragraph still opens with \"The belief\" — was that something you chose not to change, or did you miss it?"}],"stopReason":"stop","api":"ollama","provider":"ollama","model":"minimax-m2.7:cloud","usage":{"input":50959,"output":440,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":51399,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"timestamp":1775888813796}}
