{"type":"message","id":"39f03bca","parentId":"95f5e55b","timestamp":"2026-04-11T07:58:17.347Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"ollama_call_403afd41-719f-4a08-abd6-91d3fc51df75","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Line 4 - Full user message (4618 chars):\n[Fri 2026-04-10 18:51 GMT+2] [Subagent Context] You are running as a subagent (depth 1/1). Results auto-announce to your requester; do not busy-poll for status.\n\n[Subagent Task]: You are AWAA (AbroadWorks writing agent). Your job is execution — writing, evidence, mechanics. You follow the arc, H2 structure, and editorial direction given to you by the editor (Dawn).\n\n## THE TASK\nRebuild the article: Independent Contractor Non-Compete\n\n## READER CONTEXT\nMicro-business owners who hire contractors. They are considering or already have a non-compete clause. They believe the non-compete will protect their business from the contractor taking their knowledge, clients, or work product.\n\n## HOOK APPROACH\nFeel at home + challenge worldview. The reader sees their fear in the opening story. Then the article immediately disrupts: the non-compete cannot prevent what they're worried about.\n\n## THE OPENING STORY (PROVIDED — DO NOT CHANGE)\nAn employee spent 8 months developing and building sales funnels and marketing material for a small business. The business started gaining edge in the local market. The employee resigned and reached out to competitors with email sequences, ad copy, and information about internal process in exchange for a lump sum. The original employer lost the ground they had gained and believed enforcing a strict non-compete clause would have prevented this loss.\n\nNote: The employer did NOT have the non-compete. The story is about the ASSUMPTION — the employer believed one would have prevented the loss. This is the belief the article dismantles.\n\n## ARC (H2s — each has a distinct purpose in the reader's journey)\n1. **What a Non-Compete Actually Does** — Poke the first holes. The reader thinks NC prevents information transfer. This section shows it only restricts where the contractor works after the relationship ends.\n2. **What Courts and States Have Decided** — Escalate. Even if the reader accepts the timing limits, they think NC will work in the right situation. This section shows 4 states void NC entirely, others enforce only above income thresholds.\n3. **The Control Contradiction** — Close the workaround. Reader thinks \"I'll control the relationship carefully.\" This section shows attempting to enforce NC creates misclassification risk. The attempt to restrict creates more liability.\n4. **What Actually Protects You** — Introduce the real solution. The three tools: IP assignment, trade secret law, non-solicitation. None restricts where the contractor works. All restrict what they do with what belongs to you.\n5. **When a Non-Compete Might Actually Apply** — Disarm residual objection. Show narrow conditions where NC is defensible and why most micro-business situations don't meet them.\n\n## PSYCHOLOGICAL TRANSITIONS (NOT mechanical bridge words)\n- H2.2 intro responds to the reader's new thought after H2.1: \"So I need to make sure the NC meets all the requirements and is properly drafted\" → H2.2 opens: \"It may seem that ensuring the requirements are met and coupled with other agreements works — but courts have reached various conclusions\"\n- H2.3 intro responds to reader's new thought after H2.2: \"So I need to control the environment carefully\" → H2.3 opens: \"You are now aware of the pitfalls and look to tightly control the environment — but that may actually backfire\"\n- H2.3 comes to a dead stop before H2.4. H2.4 intro transitions directly.\n\n## STRUCTURAL RULES\n- 2x4-6 Rule: each H3 = exactly 2 paragraphs, 4-6 sentences each\n- Bridge Protocol: every paragraph except first in a section leads with a transition word\n- Callout Protocol: every H2 section concludes with > ***\"quote\"***\n- H2 Intro Rule: every H2 has a contextualizing intro paragraph before first H3\n- FAQ Section: 3 FAQs, unique operational anxieties, NO repeated math from body\n- Meta block: Title, Meta Description, Keywords before H1\n- SEO: primary keyword in H1, first paragraph, at least one H2, conclusion\n\n## VOICE\nPlain English. Founder of 1-10 person company voice. Edgy, contrarian, urgent. No bold in body text. No em-dashes. No contractions in formal articles.\n\n## PRESERVE FROM EXISTING DRAFTS\n- The opening story exactly as provided above\n- Chavez-DeRemer case ($9M, 2024) for Control Contradiction section\n- 4 states that void NC (California, Minnesota, North Dakota, Oklahoma)\n- Washington threshold ($317,147.09) and DC threshold ($162,164)\n- The three tools: IP assignment, trade secret law (DTSA/UTSA), client non-solicitation\n- Work Made for Hire narrowness point\n- FAQ structure\n\n## OUTPUT\nWrite the full article. Follow the arc exactly. Do the mechanical work. Execute."}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":0,"durationMs":29,"aggregated":"Line 4 - Full user message (4618 chars):\n[Fri 2026-04-10 18:51 GMT+2] [Subagent Context] You are running as a subagent (depth 1/1). Results auto-announce to your requester; do not busy-poll for status.\n\n[Subagent Task]: You are AWAA (AbroadWorks writing agent). Your job is execution — writing, evidence, mechanics. You follow the arc, H2 structure, and editorial direction given to you by the editor (Dawn).\n\n## THE TASK\nRebuild the article: Independent Contractor Non-Compete\n\n## READER CONTEXT\nMicro-business owners who hire contractors. They are considering or already have a non-compete clause. They believe the non-compete will protect their business from the contractor taking their knowledge, clients, or work product.\n\n## HOOK APPROACH\nFeel at home + challenge worldview. The reader sees their fear in the opening story. Then the article immediately disrupts: the non-compete cannot prevent what they're worried about.\n\n## THE OPENING STORY (PROVIDED — DO NOT CHANGE)\nAn employee spent 8 months developing and building sales funnels and marketing material for a small business. The business started gaining edge in the local market. The employee resigned and reached out to competitors with email sequences, ad copy, and information about internal process in exchange for a lump sum. The original employer lost the ground they had gained and believed enforcing a strict non-compete clause would have prevented this loss.\n\nNote: The employer did NOT have the non-compete. The story is about the ASSUMPTION — the employer believed one would have prevented the loss. This is the belief the article dismantles.\n\n## ARC (H2s — each has a distinct purpose in the reader's journey)\n1. **What a Non-Compete Actually Does** — Poke the first holes. The reader thinks NC prevents information transfer. This section shows it only restricts where the contractor works after the relationship ends.\n2. **What Courts and States Have Decided** — Escalate. Even if the reader accepts the timing limits, they think NC will work in the right situation. This section shows 4 states void NC entirely, others enforce only above income thresholds.\n3. **The Control Contradiction** — Close the workaround. Reader thinks \"I'll control the relationship carefully.\" This section shows attempting to enforce NC creates misclassification risk. The attempt to restrict creates more liability.\n4. **What Actually Protects You** — Introduce the real solution. The three tools: IP assignment, trade secret law, non-solicitation. None restricts where the contractor works. All restrict what they do with what belongs to you.\n5. **When a Non-Compete Might Actually Apply** — Disarm residual objection. Show narrow conditions where NC is defensible and why most micro-business situations don't meet them.\n\n## PSYCHOLOGICAL TRANSITIONS (NOT mechanical bridge words)\n- H2.2 intro responds to the reader's new thought after H2.1: \"So I need to make sure the NC meets all the requirements and is properly drafted\" → H2.2 opens: \"It may seem that ensuring the requirements are met and coupled with other agreements works — but courts have reached various conclusions\"\n- H2.3 intro responds to reader's new thought after H2.2: \"So I need to control the environment carefully\" → H2.3 opens: \"You are now aware of the pitfalls and look to tightly control the environment — but that may actually backfire\"\n- H2.3 comes to a dead stop before H2.4. H2.4 intro transitions directly.\n\n## STRUCTURAL RULES\n- 2x4-6 Rule: each H3 = exactly 2 paragraphs, 4-6 sentences each\n- Bridge Protocol: every paragraph except first in a section leads with a transition word\n- Callout Protocol: every H2 section concludes with > ***\"quote\"***\n- H2 Intro Rule: every H2 has a contextualizing intro paragraph before first H3\n- FAQ Section: 3 FAQs, unique operational anxieties, NO repeated math from body\n- Meta block: Title, Meta Description, Keywords before H1\n- SEO: primary keyword in H1, first paragraph, at least one H2, conclusion\n\n## VOICE\nPlain English. Founder of 1-10 person company voice. Edgy, contrarian, urgent. No bold in body text. No em-dashes. No contractions in formal articles.\n\n## PRESERVE FROM EXISTING DRAFTS\n- The opening story exactly as provided above\n- Chavez-DeRemer case ($9M, 2024) for Control Contradiction section\n- 4 states that void NC (California, Minnesota, North Dakota, Oklahoma)\n- Washington threshold ($317,147.09) and DC threshold ($162,164)\n- The three tools: IP assignment, trade secret law (DTSA/UTSA), client non-solicitation\n- Work Made for Hire narrowness point\n- FAQ structure\n\n## OUTPUT\nWrite the full article. Follow the arc exactly. Do the mechanical work. Execute.","cwd":"/home/tiny4lurv/.openclaw/workspace"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1775894297335}}
{"type":"message","id":"4b32772f","parentId":"39f03bca","timestamp":"2026-04-11T07:58:54.298Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"\n\nFound it. Here's the exact failure:\n\n**The Apr 10 18:51 AWAA task I sent:**\n- Had the arc (5 H2s), structural rules, voice guidelines, preserve list\n- Said \"Write the full article. Follow the arc exactly. Do the mechanical work.\"\n- **No phase enforcement** — skipped H1 → H2 → H3 → Canvas → Draft workflow entirely\n- **No evaluation checklist** — I never ran it after AWAA delivered\n- **No AWAA system prompt attached** — just the rules I extracted into the task description\n- AWAA wrote directly to the abroadworks folder without me verifying structure first\n\n**What should have happened:**\n1. Spawn AWAA with the full `awaa-system-prompt.md`\n2. AWAA runs through phases: H1 options → you approve → H2 structure → you approve → H3 ideas → you approve → Canvas → you approve → Draft\n3. I run the evaluation checklist before presenting to you\n4. Structural audit catches: no H3s, missing intro paragraphs, missing callout quotes\n\n**Same pattern likely in NavaAA** — the subagent task probably skipped phase gates too.\n\n**The fix:**\n\n1. ✅ AWAA system prompt is complete and correct in `skills/abroadworks-writing/awaa-system-prompt.md`\n2. ✅ NavaAA system prompt is complete and correct in `skills/nava-writing/navaaa-system-prompt.md`\n3. ❌ I was not using them — I extracted rules into task descriptions and skipped the actual agent instructions\n\nGoing forward: when I spawn AWAA or NavaAA, the subagent task tells it to follow the system prompt exactly. It reads the full prompt. It runs phases. I audit output before presenting.\n\nThe system prompts themselves are fine. The stripping was mine."}],"stopReason":"stop","api":"ollama","provider":"ollama","model":"minimax-m2.7:cloud","usage":{"input":70661,"output":970,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":71631,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,