{"type":"message","id":"6e55437c","parentId":"6597c482","timestamp":"2026-04-11T08:04:02.964Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"ollama_call_7b20e420-6ca5-4c6b-b98a-8ba7490ac54b","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"[Fri 2026-04-10 20:21 GMT+2] [Subagent Context] You are running as a subagent (depth 1/1). Results auto-announce to your requester; do not busy-poll for status.\n\n[Subagent Task]: You are AWAA (AbroadWorks Article Architect). Your job is to review and stress-test an annotated article outline before drafting begins.\n\n## TOPIC\nIndependent Contractor Non-Compete: What It Actually Covers (and What It Doesn't)\n\n## CURRENT DRAFT STATUS\nv7 exists (12,959 bytes, 5 H2s). Tiny has flagged that H2.1 (what it does) and H2.2 (courts/states) deal with the same subject and should merge. He also wants H2.3 to potentially absorb more examples from the source material as separate H3s.\n\n## PROPOSED ANNOTATED OUTLINE (4 H2s, 12 H3s)\n\n**H1:** Independent Contractor Non-Compete: What It Actually Covers (and What It Doesn't)\n\n**H2.1 — The Promise and the Gap** *(what the clause actually is, what it covers, why enforceability varies)*\n- H3.1.1 — What the clause actually restricts (post-relationship location only)\n- H3.1.2 — The enforceability landscape (4 void states, 2 threshold jurisdictions, the rest vary)\n- H3.1.3 — Why the geographic patchwork makes the protection feel absolute when it isn't\n\n**H2.2 — The Control Contradiction** *(the central disruption — enforcement creates its own liability)*\n- H3.2.1 — The mechanism: enforcement becomes the evidence of misclassification\n- H3.2.2 — The Chavez-DeRemer case: $9M judgment where the non-compete was the exhibit, not the primary liability\n- H3.2.3 — The irony: the more you try to protect, the more you demonstrate economic dependence\n\n**H2.3 — What Actually Protects You** *(the solution section)*\n- H3.3.1 — IP assignment: the foundation most agreements skip\n- H3.3.2 — Trade secret law: federal, state-robust, covers the information problem\n- H3.3.3 — Non-solicitation: the clause that actually targets client relationships\n\n**H2.4 — When It Might Be Worth Using** *(closes the loop, earns its place briefly)*\n- H3.4.1 — The narrow scenario where it holds (threshold met + genuine independence + narrow scope)\n- H3.4.2 — The real question to ask your provider\n\n## YOUR TASK\n1. Read this outline carefully\n2. Identify any structural problems: sections that could overlap, H3s that don't have distinct jobs, gaps in the reader's arc\n3. Flag if any H3 could swap into a different H2 without the article breaking\n4. Note if any section needs a different number of H3s (source material may support more or fewer)\n5. Comment on whether the arc (Promise → Disruption → Solution → Closing) is clear and earns the reader's journey\n\nDo NOT produce any draft content. Only structural/arc commentary on the outline above. Be specific: if something is wrong, say what exactly and why. If something works, say briefly why.\n\nStart with your structural analysis now."}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":0,"durationMs":34,"aggregated":"[Fri 2026-04-10 20:21 GMT+2] [Subagent Context] You are running as a subagent (depth 1/1). Results auto-announce to your requester; do not busy-poll for status.\n\n[Subagent Task]: You are AWAA (AbroadWorks Article Architect). Your job is to review and stress-test an annotated article outline before drafting begins.\n\n## TOPIC\nIndependent Contractor Non-Compete: What It Actually Covers (and What It Doesn't)\n\n## CURRENT DRAFT STATUS\nv7 exists (12,959 bytes, 5 H2s). Tiny has flagged that H2.1 (what it does) and H2.2 (courts/states) deal with the same subject and should merge. He also wants H2.3 to potentially absorb more examples from the source material as separate H3s.\n\n## PROPOSED ANNOTATED OUTLINE (4 H2s, 12 H3s)\n\n**H1:** Independent Contractor Non-Compete: What It Actually Covers (and What It Doesn't)\n\n**H2.1 — The Promise and the Gap** *(what the clause actually is, what it covers, why enforceability varies)*\n- H3.1.1 — What the clause actually restricts (post-relationship location only)\n- H3.1.2 — The enforceability landscape (4 void states, 2 threshold jurisdictions, the rest vary)\n- H3.1.3 — Why the geographic patchwork makes the protection feel absolute when it isn't\n\n**H2.2 — The Control Contradiction** *(the central disruption — enforcement creates its own liability)*\n- H3.2.1 — The mechanism: enforcement becomes the evidence of misclassification\n- H3.2.2 — The Chavez-DeRemer case: $9M judgment where the non-compete was the exhibit, not the primary liability\n- H3.2.3 — The irony: the more you try to protect, the more you demonstrate economic dependence\n\n**H2.3 — What Actually Protects You** *(the solution section)*\n- H3.3.1 — IP assignment: the foundation most agreements skip\n- H3.3.2 — Trade secret law: federal, state-robust, covers the information problem\n- H3.3.3 — Non-solicitation: the clause that actually targets client relationships\n\n**H2.4 — When It Might Be Worth Using** *(closes the loop, earns its place briefly)*\n- H3.4.1 — The narrow scenario where it holds (threshold met + genuine independence + narrow scope)\n- H3.4.2 — The real question to ask your provider\n\n## YOUR TASK\n1. Read this outline carefully\n2. Identify any structural problems: sections that could overlap, H3s that don't have distinct jobs, gaps in the reader's arc\n3. Flag if any H3 could swap into a different H2 without the article breaking\n4. Note if any section needs a different number of H3s (source material may support more or fewer)\n5. Comment on whether the arc (Promise → Disruption → Solution → Closing) is clear and earns the reader's journey\n\nDo NOT produce any draft content. Only structural/arc commentary on the outline above. Be specific: if something is wrong, say what exactly and why. If something works, say briefly why.\n\nStart with your structural analysis now.","cwd":"/home/tiny4lurv/.openclaw/workspace"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1775894642954}}
{"type":"message","id":"df1afe9e","parentId":"6e55437c","timestamp":"2026-04-11T08:04:13.118Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"toolCall","id":"ollama_call_a3f8f089-6768-42f1-b330-7d66ae0e6d5d","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"python3 << 'EOF'\nimport json\n\n# Read line 5 - AWAA's response\nfpath = '/home/tiny4lurv/.openclaw/agents/main/sessions/bb566052-4894-474d-8e27-2e24187f9f3d.jsonl'\nwith open(fpath) as f:\n    lines = f.readlines()\n\nfor i, line in enumerate(lines):\n    if i == 5:\n        obj = json.loads(line)\n        msg = obj.get('message', {})\n        content = msg.get('content', [])\n        if isinstance(content, list) and content:\n            full_text = content[0].get('text', '')\n            print(full_text)\nEOF"}}],"stopReason":"toolUse","api":"ollama","provider":"ollama","model":"minimax-m2.7:cloud","usage":{"input":69910,"output":232,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":70142,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"timestamp":1775894653118}}
{"type":"message","id":"36716864","parentId":"df1afe9e","timestamp":"2026-04-11T08:04:13.168Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"ollama_call_a3f8f089-6768-42f1-b330-7d66ae0e6d5d","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"## AWAA Structural Analysis: Non-Compete Article Outline\n\n### What Works\n\n**The arc holds.** Promise → Disruption → Solution → Closing is a sound structure, and 4 H2s is the right count for this topic. Twelve H3s across four sections is also reasonable — dense but not bloated for a ~10k-word explainer.\n\n**H2.2's internal structure is clean.** H3.2.1 (mechanism), H3.2.2 (case study), H3.2.3 (irony thesis) is a good escalation — concept, proof, landing take. Each H3 has a distinct job and they're sequential, not parallel.\n\n**H2.4 earns its place.** Two H3s is right for a closing section. It doesn't overclaim.\n\n---\n\n### Structural Problems\n\n**Problem 1 — H2.1 and H2.2 share a subject but the distinction between them is unclear.**\n\nH2.1 covers what non-competes cover and why they're enforced variably. H2.2 covers the problem with trying to enforce them. But H3.1.2 (enforceability landscape) and H2.2's core argument are describing adjacent facets of the same phenomenon — the gap between what the clause says and what actually happens when you try to use it. After reading H2.1's enforceability landscape, the reader already knows enforcement is uncertain. H2.2 then arrives and says \"enforcement creates liability.\" That's actually a new, different point — but the outline doesn't make that distinction clear enough.\n\nIf Tiny wants to merge H2.1 and H2.2, the combined section would need a clearer through-line: *what it covers → why enforcement is unreliable → why enforcement makes things worse.* The danger is that merging produces a longer H2 that reads as two sections stapled together rather than one argument.\n\n**Problem 2 — H3.1.2 and H3.1.3 are doing overlapping work.**\n\nH3.1.2 describes the enforceability landscape (4 void states, 2 threshold, rest vary). H3.1.3 asks why the patchwork makes the protection feel absolute when it isn't. But H3.1.3 is essentially the *reader takeaway* from H3.1.2 — it doesn't add new information, it interprets it. These could collapse into a single H3: \"The enforceability landscape — and why knowing it doesn't make you safe.\" That would free up a slot for something with more substance, if source material supports it.\n\n**Problem 3 — H3.2.3 (the irony) is functioning as a section conclusion, not a standalone H3.**\n\n\"**The irony: the more you try to protect, the more you demonstrate economic dependence**\" is the landing punch of H2.2. It works as the final beat — but it's not really building a separate argument from H3.2.1 or H3.2.2. It summarizes them. If this moves to H2.4 (as the broader lesson) that's cleaner. If it stays in H2.2, the outline should make clear it's the concluding H3, not a third independent point.\n\n**Problem 4 — H2.3's three H3s don't all land at the same level.**\n\nH3.3.1 (IP assignment) and H3.3.3 (non-solicitation) are contractual clauses — things you write into agreements. H3.3.2 (trade secret law) is statutory — a legal framework you don't need to create, just invoke. These are fundamentally different kinds of protection. The section reads as \"here's what actually protects you\" but the reader might wonder: is trade secret law something I put in a contract or something that just exists? The distinction needs to be visible in the outline, or one H3 needs to be reframed to make the difference clear.\n\n---\n\n### H3 Swappability Flags\n\n**H3.1.3 could potentially move to H2.4** as the \"what you should actually conclude\" without breaking anything. It's more of a synthesis observation than a standalone factual point.\n\n**H3.2.3 could potentially move to H2.4** for the same reason — it's a conclusion masquerading as an argument.\n\nThe risk of moving either: H2.4 already has 2 H3s. Adding a third makes it feel heavy compared to the other sections. If one of these migrates, consider whether H2.4 actually needs 3, or whether one of its current H3s absorbs the migrated content.\n\n---\n\n### Gaps\n\n**The article doesn't explicitly address the threshold question until H2.4.** But H3.1.2 mentions \"2 threshold jurisdictions\" — which implies some states only enforce non-competes if certain conditions are met (income thresholds, specialty roles, etc.). This is important enough that it might warrant its own H3 under H2.1, rather than being buried in a list. The threshold concept is where a lot of practitioners get tripped up, and it's conceptually distinct from \"4 states void them entirely.\"\n\n**No H3 addresses what clients/employers actually want protected.** The article explains what non-competes do and don't protect, but doesn't explicitly state the underlying concern: client relationships, proprietary knowledge, competitive moat. The solution section (H2.3) implies this, but the reader doesn't see the problem stated until H2.4's narrow-scenario framing. That's a gap in the promise section — the article says \"here's what the clause promises\" without first making explicit what the client is actually trying to protect.\n\n---\n\n### Recommended Adjustments\n\n1. **Redistribute H3.1.3** — merge it into H3.1.2 or move it to H2.4.\n2. **Add a standalone H3 on thresholds** — or clarify in H3.1.2 that threshold jurisdictions are a distinct category with their own logic, not just another data point in the patchwork.\n3. **Clarify the merged H2.1/2.2 through-line** — if merged, the section needs a single organizing question, not two parallel tracks.\n4. **Separate IP assignment and trade secret law by type** — make clear one is contractual, one is statutory, so the reader understands the mechanism difference.\n\nThe arc works. The problems are in the middle sections where H3s overlap or don't have clearly distinct jobs. Addressing those three items would strengthen the outline before drafting begins."}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":0,"durationMs":34,"aggregated":"## AWAA Structural Analysis: Non-Compete Article Outline\n\n### What Works\n\n**The arc holds.** Promise → Disruption → Solution → Closing is a sound structure, and 4 H2s is the right count for this topic. Twelve H3s across four sections is also reasonable — dense but not bloated for a ~10k-word explainer.\n\n**H2.2's internal structure is clean.** H3.2.1 (mechanism), H3.2.2 (case study), H3.2.3 (irony thesis) is a good escalation — concept, proof, landing take. Each H3 has a distinct job and they're sequential, not parallel.\n\n**H2.4 earns its place.** Two H3s is right for a closing section. It doesn't overclaim.\n\n---\n\n### Structural Problems\n\n**Problem 1 — H2.1 and H2.2 share a subject but the distinction between them is unclear.**\n\nH2.1 covers what non-competes cover and why they're enforced variably. H2.2 covers the problem with trying to enforce them. But H3.1.2 (enforceability landscape) and H2.2's core argument are describing adjacent facets of the same phenomenon — the gap between what the clause says and what actually happens when you try to use it. After reading H2.1's enforceability landscape, the reader already knows enforcement is uncertain. H2.2 then arrives and says \"enforcement creates liability.\" That's actually a new, different point — but the outline doesn't make that distinction clear enough.\n\nIf Tiny wants to merge H2.1 and H2.2, the combined section would need a clearer through-line: *what it covers → why enforcement is unreliable → why enforcement makes things worse.* The danger is that merging produces a longer H2 that reads as two sections stapled together rather than one argument.\n\n**Problem 2 — H3.1.2 and H3.1.3 are doing overlapping work.**\n\nH3.1.2 describes the enforceability landscape (4 void states, 2 threshold, rest vary). H3.1.3 asks why the patchwork makes the protection feel absolute when it isn't. But H3.1.3 is essentially the *reader takeaway* from H3.1.2 — it doesn't add new information, it interprets it. These could collapse into a single H3: \"The enforceability landscape — and why knowing it doesn't make you safe.\" That would free up a slot for something with more substance, if source material supports it.\n\n**Problem 3 — H3.2.3 (the irony) is functioning as a section conclusion, not a standalone H3.**\n\n\"**The irony: the more you try to protect, the more you demonstrate economic dependence**\" is the landing punch of H2.2. It works as the final beat — but it's not really building a separate argument from H3.2.1 or H3.2.2. It summarizes them. If this moves to H2.4 (as the broader lesson) that's cleaner. If it stays in H2.2, the outline should make clear it's the concluding H3, not a third independent point.\n\n**Problem 4 — H2.3's three H3s don't all land at the same level.**\n\nH3.3.1 (IP assignment) and H3.3.3 (non-solicitation) are contractual clauses — things you write into agreements. H3.3.2 (trade secret law) is statutory — a legal framework you don't need to create, just invoke. These are fundamentally different kinds of protection. The section reads as \"here's what actually protects you\" but the reader might wonder: is trade secret law something I put in a contract or something that just exists? The distinction needs to be visible in the outline, or one H3 needs to be reframed to make the difference clear.\n\n---\n\n### H3 Swappability Flags\n\n**H3.1.3 could potentially move to H2.4** as the \"what you should actually conclude\" without breaking anything. It's more of a synthesis observation than a standalone factual point.\n\n**H3.2.3 could potentially move to H2.4** for the same reason — it's a conclusion masquerading as an argument.\n\nThe risk of moving either: H2.4 already has 2 H3s. Adding a third makes it feel heavy compared to the other sections. If one of these migrates, consider whether H2.4 actually needs 3, or whether one of its current H3s absorbs the migrated content.\n\n---\n\n### Gaps\n\n**The article doesn't explicitly address the threshold question until H2.4.** But H3.1.2 mentions \"2 threshold jurisdictions\" — which implies some states only enforce non-competes if certain conditions are met (income thresholds, specialty roles, etc.). This is important enough that it might warrant its own H3 under H2.1, rather than being buried in a list. The threshold concept is where a lot of practitioners get tripped up, and it's conceptually distinct from \"4 states void them entirely.\"\n\n**No H3 addresses what clients/employers actually want protected.** The article explains what non-competes do and don't protect, but doesn't explicitly state the underlying concern: client relationships, proprietary knowledge, competitive moat. The solution section (H2.3) implies this, but the reader doesn't see the problem stated until H2.4's narrow-scenario framing. That's a gap in the promise section — the article says \"here's what the clause promises\" without first making explicit what the client is actually trying to protect.\n\n---\n\n### Recommended Adjustments\n\n1. **Redistribute H3.1.3** — merge it into H3.1.2 or move it to H2.4.\n2. **Add a standalone H3 on thresholds** — or clarify in H3.1.2 that threshold jurisdictions are a distinct category with their own logic, not just another data point in the patchwork.\n3. **Clarify the merged H2.1/2.2 through-line** — if merged, the section needs a single organizing question, not two parallel tracks.\n4. **Separate IP assignment and trade secret law by type** — make clear one is contractual, one is statutory, so the reader understands the mechanism difference.\n\nThe arc works. The problems are in the middle sections where H3s overlap or don't have clearly distinct jobs. Addressing those three items would strengthen the outline before drafting begins.","cwd":"/home/tiny4lurv/.openclaw/workspace"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1775894653160}}
{"type":"message","id":"7bc6558d","parentId":"36716864","timestamp":"2026-04-11T08:04:30.387Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"toolCall","id":"ollama_call_a67ccc52-c9d2-4384-a99f-d343886b28c8","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"python3 << 'EOF'\nimport json\n\n# Search for \"full autonomy\" in all session files\nimport glob\nsession_dir = '/home/tiny4lurv/.openclaw/agents/main/sessions/'\n\nfor fpath in sorted(glob.glob(session_dir + '*.jsonl')):\n    fname = fpath.split('/')[-1]\n    with open(fpath) as f:\n        lines = f.readlines()\n    \n    for i, line in enumerate(lines):\n        obj = json.loads(line)\n        if obj.get('type') == 'message':\n            msg = obj.get('message', {})\n            content = msg.get('content', [])\n            if isinstance(content, list) and content:\n                text = content[0].get('text', '')\n                if text and 'autonomy' in text.lower():\n                    print(f\"\\n=== {fname} line {i} ===\")\n                    print(text[:500])\nEOF"}}],"stopReason":"toolUse","api":"ollama","provider":"ollama","model":"minimax-m2.7:cloud","usage":{"input":67503,"output":271,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":67774,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"timestamp":1775894670387}}
