{"type":"message","id":"48154678","parentId":"0e161fe8","timestamp":"2026-04-11T08:05:42.743Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"\n\nHere's the annotated outline Tiny approved (from Apr 10 18:21 session):\n\n---\n\n**H1:** Independent Contractor Non-Compete: What It Actually Covers (and What It Doesn't)\n\n**H2.1 — The Promise and the Gap** *(what the clause actually is, what it covers, why enforceability varies)*\n- H3.1.1 — What the clause actually restricts (post-relationship location only)\n- H3.1.2 — The enforceability landscape (4 void states, 2 threshold jurisdictions, the rest vary)\n- H3.1.3 — Why the geographic patchwork makes the protection feel absolute when it isn't\n\n**H2.2 — The Control Contradiction** *(the central disruption — enforcement creates its own liability)*\n- H3.2.1 — The mechanism: enforcement becomes the evidence of misclassification\n- H3.2.2 — The Chavez-DeRemer case: $9M judgment where the non-compete was the exhibit, not the primary liability\n- H3.2.3 — The irony: the more you try to protect, the more you demonstrate economic dependence\n\n**H2.3 — What Actually Protects You** *(the solution section)*\n- H3.3.1 — IP assignment: the foundation most agreements skip\n- H3.3.2 — Trade secret law: federal, state-robust, covers the information problem\n- H3.3.3 — Non-solicitation: the clause that actually targets client relationships\n\n**H2.4 — When It Might Be Worth Using** *(closes the loop, earns its place briefly)*\n- H3.4.1 — The narrow scenario where it holds (threshold met + genuine independence + narrow scope)\n- H3.4.2 — The real question to ask your provider\n\n---\n\n**4 H2s, 12 H3s, arc: Promise → Disruption → Solution → Closing**\n\nThe AWAA run at 18:05 produced 5 H2s — I had compressed the outline into the task without the H3 nesting. Then I presented the output without auditing the structure. You said \"full autonomy\" meaning I make the normal decisions you'd defer to me — not that I skip t