 record of your awareness of it.\n*Pivot: If your contractor's departure would genuinely harm your business, that is a business model problem that a non-compete cannot fix.*\n\n---\n\n**H2.3 — What Actually Protects You**\n\n**H3.3.1 — IP assignment**\nP1: Copyright and IP assignment directly transfers ownership of work product to your business from the moment of creation. This answers \"can they use what they built for me against me?\" Explicit assignment means the work stays yours when the relationship ends.\nP2: Work made for hire applies narrow. For most contractor relationships, an explicit IP assignment clause is the operative mechanism. Most agreements skip this or bury it in definitional sections.\n*Pivot: What does your current agreement say about who owns the work product when the engagement ends, and have you ever read that section?*\n\n**H3.3.2 — Trade secret law**\nP1: DTSA (federal) and state UTSA laws protect confidential information — client lists, pricing structures, processes, methodologies — without requiring a contract clause to activate. This answers \"can they take my customer knowledge?\"\nP2: Reasonable steps means marking documents confidential, limiting access on a need-to-know basis, using NDAs where appropriate. Courts look for evidence you treated information as secret, not just described it that way in a contract.\n*Pivot: What confidential information of yours has been shared freely with contractors without any internal classification of its sensitivity?*\n\n**H3.3.3 — Non-solicitation** *(may be incomplete — transmission truncated)*\n\n---\n\n**Awaiting your approval** to proceed to Phase 5 (full draft).\n\nNote: H3.3.3 and H2.4 were cut off in transmission. I need to check whether AWAA has the full canvas before we can approve Phase 4. Want me to pull the complete output from the subagent session?"}],"stopReason":"stop","api":"ollama","provider":"ollama","model":"minimax-m2.7:cloud","usage":{"input":81387,"output":1290,"cacheRead":0,