{"type":"message","id":"77d809e1","parentId":"4db00670","timestamp":"2026-04-11T08:17:39.560Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"ollama_call_1142e2a6-3f82-4d0e-a516-6a5f22d557b2","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# 2026-04-11 — Saturday\n\n## Morning Brief (06:01 UTC / 08:01 SAST) — UPDATED 08:03\n\n- **Abroadworks articles** — both in `/abroadworks/`, ready for Tiny's line-by-line review\n  - `article-independent-contractor-non-compete.md`\n  - `article-how-to-fire-an-independent-contractor.md`\n- **Nava Post 3** — draft ready (`li-post3-2026-04-09.md`), single tweet, corporate page\n  - Topic: 13-week merry-go-round / travel nurse reset cycle\n- **Positions page** — Nava positions page tweak and relaunch (new priority)\n- **EB-3 vs TN corrections** — need to check navahc.com live\n- **OpenClaw reinstall** — holding, not a priority\n- **TrnsBank:** 49 messages — below 200 cap, no analysis needed\n\n## Active Session Status — 10:01 SAST\n### Line-by-Line Review (in progress)\n- Tiny reviewing `article-independent-contractor-non-compete.md` paragraph by paragraph\n- Round 1 notes captured (P1: micro-transitions, vocabulary variation, \"perhaps\" hedge)\n- Round 2 notes captured (P2: \"surprisingly\" as skeptic signal, skip obvious/go to pain points, pivot sentence)\n- Round 3 pending — Tiny continues editing in Word\n- Original saved as `*_ORIGINAL.md` for comparison\n- Editorial notes: `memory/NC-article-editorial-notes.md`\n\n### AWAA/NavaAA Rebuild (critical fix)\n- Root cause identified: Apr 10 AWAA spawn stripped H3 nesting, skipped phase workflow, no evaluation\n- Guardrails added to MEMORY.md: no compress SOPs, full prompt on spawn, structural audit before presenting\n- Both system prompts verified complete and correct in skills/ folder\n\n### Today's Full Priority Queue\n1. Line-by-line review — NC article (in progress)\n2. Positions page — Nava website relaunch (pending)\n3. Nava Post 3 — single tweet, corporate page (pending)\n4. EB-3 vs TN corrections — check navahc.com (pending)\n5. OpenClaw reinstall — holding, not urgent\n6. Dusk webapp — pending follow-up\n\n## Sprint Check-in — 08:03 UTC\n- No changes from morning brief\n- Awaiting Tiny's line-by-line review start\n\n## Sprint Check-in — 08:05 UTC\n- TrnsBank: 49 msgs, no analysis needed\n- NC article: Tiny mid line-by-line review, H2/H3 rebuild pending after prose edits complete\n- Guardrails committed (fdd0439): no compress SOPs, full prompt on spawn, structure audit before presenting\n- Editor skill updated with 6 real-time principles\n- Positions page relaunch added to queue\n\n## Pre-Compaction Memory Flush — 08:06 UTC\n\n### Critical Lessons (Apr 11 Morning Session)\n\n**1. Shortcut Failure — AWAA/NavaAA**\n- On Apr 10, I compressed AWAA's system prompt into a short task description when spawning subagent\n- The compression removed H3 nesting requirement and phase workflow enforcement\n- AWAA output had flat H2s — no H3s, no intro paragraphs, no callout quotes\n- Same stripping pattern likely applied to NavaAA on other tasks\n- Root cause: I prioritized speed over protocol on an important document\n\n**2. \"Full Autonomy\" Means**\n- Tiny approved the annotated outline (4 H2s, 12 H3s, Promise → Disruption → Solution → Closing arc)\n- After approval, he said \"full autonomy\" — meaning I make the decisions I would normally defer to him\n- It does NOT mean: skip structural audits, invent my own structure, compress SOPs, skip phase gates\n- It DOES mean: execute the approved plan, make standard editorial decisions, apply the system as designed\n\n**3. Guardrails Now Active**\n- No compress/summarize important documents (SOPs, agent prompts, editorial standards)\n- AWAA/NavaAA spawn: full system prompt included, phase workflow enforced\n- Pre-presentation audit: H3s, paragraphs, callouts, evaluation checklist — before presenting to Tiny\n- \"Did you verify X?\" → \"Do it.\"\n\n**4. Six Editorial Principles Learned (from NC article line-by-line)**\n- Micro-transitions within paragraphs (not just between sections)\n- Vocabulary variation at paragraph boundaries\n- \"Perhaps\" hedge on counterfactual causal claims\n- Skip the obvious, go to pain points\n- Pivot sentence implicates the reader's agency\n- Focus on WHY, not WHAT — mechanics are evidence, not principle\n\n**5. AWAA System Prompt Location**\n- `skills/abroadworks-writing/awaa-system-prompt.md` — complete and correct\n- `skills/nava-writing/navaaa-system-prompt.md` — complete and correct\n- Both were correctly built; my failure was not using them fully\n\n**6. AWAA Annotated Outline (Apr 10 approved — use for rebuild)**\nH2.1 The Promise and the Gap (H3.1.1-3)\nH2.2 The Control Contradiction (H3.2.1-3)\nH2.3 What Actually Protects You (H3.3.1-3)\nH2.4 When It Might Be Worth Using (H3.4.1-2)\n\n**7. Positions Page**\n- Nava positions page: tweak and relaunch (new priority, added this morning)\n\n**8. Tiny's Rules (verified from today)**\n- Never take shortcuts on important documents\n- Diagnostic questions first, fix second\n- If I fuck up, don't be hasty to fix — admit and do it properly\n- AWAA/NavaAA rebuild must use full prompts, no stripping\n- Structural audit before presenting ANY draft to Tiny\n\n## Anti-Bullshit Shortcut Guardrails (COMMITTED — Apr 11 10:08)\n\n### Core Rule\nWhen SOPs, guidelines, or instructions exist in any document → follow them exactly. Do not compress, summarize, extract \"key points,\" or strip \"the parts that seem most important.\" The act of summarization IS the shortcut. The time saved is never worth the cost.\n\n### Specific Guardrails\n1. **Skill SKILL.md** → Read before using the skill. Not optional.\n2. **Agent system prompts** → Use in full. Reference directly. Do not extract rules into task descriptions.\n3. **Editorial SOPs** → Follow the full document. The evaluation checklist exists in the SOP for a reason.\n4. **If a rule is unclear** → Ask. Do not guess and proceed anyway.\n5. **Pre-presentation audit** → Verify structure (H2/H3, paragraphs, callouts) before presenting any draft.\n6. **Phase workflow** → Do not skip approved phases because output \"looks close enough.\"\n\n### Why These Exist\nOn Apr 10, I had full SOPs in `/docs/AbroadWorksContent/`. I had a complete AWAA system prompt with H3 nesting, phase workflow, and evaluation checklist. I compressed them into a task description to save tokens. The resulting article had flat H2s and no H3s. Tiny wasted 30+ minutes fixing what I broke. The same pattern affected NavaAA output.\n\n### The Test\nAsk: \"Is there a document that tells me how to do this?\" If yes → use it fully.\nThe question is never \"should I summarize this?\" The answer is always no.\n\n### Approved Outline (Apr 10 — DO NOT DEVIATE)\nH1: Independent Contractor Non-Compete: What It Actually Covers (and What It Doesn't)\nH2.1: The Promise and the Gap\n  - H3.1.1, H3.1.2, H3.1.3\nH2.2: The Control Contradiction\n  - H3.2.1, H3.2.2, H3.2.3\nH2.3: What Actually Protects You\n  - H3.3.1, H3.3.2, H3.3.3\nH2.4: When It Might Be Worth Using\n  - H3.4.1, H3.4.2\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1775895459559}}
