\n+159 - Session key: `agent:main:subagent:39673e80-5803-4bd7-b6a1-718581231b25`\n+160 - Status: running, awaiting Phase 4 confirmation or further instruction\n+161 - Token count: 18k in / 1.7k out for Phase 3 completion","firstChangedLine":130},"isError":false,"timestamp":1775895470154}}
{"type":"message","id":"4f2716d4","parentId":"c024ce3e","timestamp":"2026-04-11T08:17:53.898Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"\n\nNO_REPLY"}],"stopReason":"stop","api":"ollama","provider":"ollama","model":"minimax-m2.7:cloud","usage":{"input":47439,"output":222,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":47661,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"timestamp":1775895473896}}
{"type":"message","id":"c11e1e50","parentId":"4f2716d4","timestamp":"2026-04-11T08:17:54.917Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Pre-compaction memory flush. Store durable memories only in memory/2026-04-11.md (create memory/ if needed). Treat workspace bootstrap/reference files such as MEMORY.md, SOUL.md, TOOLS.md, and AGENTS.md as read-only during this flush; never overwrite, replace, or edit them. If memory/2026-04-11.md already exists, APPEND new content only and do not overwrite existing entries. Do NOT create timestamped variant files (e.g., 2026-04-11-HHMM.md); always use the canonical 2026-04-11.md filename. If nothing to store, reply with NO_REPLY.\nCurrent time: Saturday, April 11th, 2026 — 10:17 AM (Africa/Johannesburg) / 2026-04-11 08:17 UTC"}],"timestamp":1775895474911}}
{"type":"message","id":"35783fea","parentId":"c11e1e50","timestamp":"2026-04-11T08:17:56.514Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"\n\nNO_REPLY"}],"stopReason":"stop","api":"ollama","provider":"ollama","model":"minimax-m2.7:cloud","usage":{"input":47637,"output":21,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":47658,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"timestamp":1775895476514}}
{"type":"message","id":"ce73e032","parentId":"35783fea","timestamp":"2026-04-11T08:17:57.439Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Conversation info (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"message_id\": \"3EB0390EBE6D8A102C58C0\",\n  \"sender_id\": \"+27763674298\",\n  \"sender\": \"+27763674298\"\n}\n```\n\nSender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"+27763674298\",\n  \"id\": \"+27763674298\",\n  \"e164\": \"+27763674298\"\n}\n```\n\nAWAA completed Phase 4. Here's the paragraph-level canvas (truncated in transmission — H3.3.3 and H2.4 may be incomplete):\n\n---\n\n*H2.1 — The Promise and the Gap*\n\n*H3.1.1 — What the clause actually restricts*\nP1: The non-compete protects a location, not your business. It restricts where your contractor works after the relationship ends — it says nothing about the information, methodologies, or client data they generated. The gap is structural.\nP2: The information walks out the door regardless. Eight months of funnel builds, email sequences, process docs — none addressed by \"shall not perform services within 50 miles.\" The non-compete was never designed to solve the problem the reader thinks they're solving.\n*Pivot: When you signed that clause, what were you actually trying to stop, and does the language you signed actually stop it?*\n\n*H3.1.2 — The enforceability landscape*\nP1: California, Minnesota, North Dakota, Oklahoma — non-competes are entirely unenforceable regardless of contract language. Not weak — worthless. This is not a drafting problem.\nP2: Washington ($317,147.09 threshold) and DC ($162,164) add financial gates. Below the threshold, the clause cannot be enforced regardless of contract language. These thresholds are not advertised in contract templates.\n*Pivot: Do you know which jurisdiction your contractor is working from, and does it change everything you thought you had protected?*\n\n*H3.1.3 — The geographic patchwork illusion*\nP1: The non-compete looks solid — legal language, geographic radius, defined terms. The illusion: complexity creates the impression of proportional protection. It does not.\nP2: A clause that appears ironclad in New York is tissue paper in California. The contractor can move tomorrow. Your assumption about jurisdiction may not match reality.\n*Pivot: Which version of enforceability applies to your contractor, and do you know which one you are holding?*\n\n---\n\n*H2.2 — The Control Contradiction*\n\n*H3.2.1 — The mechanism*\nP1: Attempting to enforce your non-compete reveals the underlying economic relationship. If you're dictating hours, requiring your systems, controlling method — you're treating them as an employee. The non-compete is a document that exists precisely because you are.\nP2: Worker classification is determined by economic reality, not contract language. A non-compete demonstrates behavioral control inconsistent with independence. The harder you push it, the more you reveal the degree of integration.\n*Pivot: When you go to enforce this clause, what version of your business relationship are you going to court to defend?*\n\n*H3.2.2 — The Chavez-DeRemer case ($9M)*\nP1: The primary liability was worker misclassification, not the non-compete. The non-compete was introduced as evidence of behavioral control inconsistent with independence. It was the exhibit, not the charge.\nP2: The $9M was the cost of underlying misclassification liability, compounded by the fact that the company had restricted contractor movement in writing. That restriction was the proof the business was organized around controlling workers it claimed were independent.\n*Pivot: The next time you consider adding a non-compete, ask what that document will say about your relationship if it ends up in discovery.*\n\n*H3.2.3 — The dependence signal*\nP1: Genuinely independent contractors compete freely — their business doesn't depend on yours. A business with a genuinely independent contractor doesn't need a non-compete. The need for one is a diagnostic signal about the degree of integration.\nP2: The more embedded a contractor is in your operations, the more your relationship looks like employment. You have a financial dependence problem. The non-compete doesn't change the underlying economic reality — it creates a record of your awareness of it.\n*Pivot: If your contractor's departure would genuinely harm your business, that is a business model problem that a non-compete cannot fix.*\n\n---"}],"timestamp":1775895477433}}
{"type":"message","id":"5deaa339","parentId":"ce73e032","timestamp":"2026-04-11T08:18:10.754Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"That's my Phase 4 summary — AWAA's output was truncated. Let me pull the full canvas from the subagent session now.\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"ollama_call_b1404ebf-f6b9-45d1-93c8-aa33615584c0","name":"sessions_history","arguments":{"sessionKey":"agent:main:subagent:39673e80-5803-4bd7-b6a1-718581231b25","limit":10}}],"stopReason":"toolUse","api":"ollama","provider":"ollama","model":"minimax-m2.7:cloud","usage":{"input":46169,"output":337,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":46506,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"timestamp":1775895490752}}
{"type":"message","id":"62539d1f","parentId":"5deaa339","timestamp":"2026-04-11T08:18:10.847Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"ollama_call_b1404ebf-f6b9-45d1-93c8-aa33615584c0","toolName":"sessions_history","content":[{"type":"text","text":"{\n  \"sessionKey\": \"agent:main:subagent:39673e80-5803-4bd7-b6a1-718581231b25\",\n  \"messages\": [\n    {\n      \"role\": \"user\",\n      \"content\": [\n        {\n          \"type\": \"text\",\n          \"text\": \"[Subagent Context] You are running as a subagent (depth 1/1). Results auto-announce to your requester; do not busy-poll for status.\\n\\n[Subagent Task]: You are AWAA (AbroadWorks Article Architect). Read your full system prompt at `/home/tiny4lurv/.openclaw/workspace/skills/abroadworks-writing/awaa-system-prompt.md` before doing anything else. Follow it exactly.\\n\\n## APPROVED OUTLINE (from Tiny — Apr 10)\\nThis outline was approved. Do not deviate from it.\\n\\n**H1:** Independent Contractor Non-Compete: What It Actually Covers (and What It Doesn't)\\n\\n**H2.1 — The Promise and the Gap** *(what the clause actually is, what it covers, why enforceability varies)*\\n- H3.1.1 — What the clause actually restricts (post-relationship location only)\\n- H3.1.2 — The enforceability landscape (4 void states, 2 threshold jurisdictions, the rest vary)\\n- H3.1.3 — Why the geographic patchwork makes the protection feel absolute when it isn't\\n\\n**H2.2 — The Control Contradiction** *(the central disruption — enforcement creates its own liability)*\\n- H3.2.1 — The mechanism: enforcement becomes the evidence of misclassification\\n- H3.2.2 — The Chavez-DeRemer case: $9M judgment where the non-compete was the exhibit, not the primary liability\\n- H3.2.3 — The irony: the more you try to protect, the more you demonstrate economic dependence\\n\\n**H2.3 — What Actually Protects You** *(the solution section)*\\n- H3.3.1 — IP assignment: the foundation most agreements skip\\n- H3.3.2 — Trade secret law: federal, state-robust, covers the information problem\\n- H3.3.3 — Non-solicitation: the clause that actually targets client relationships\\n\\n**H2.4 — When It Might Be Worth Using** *(closes the loop, earns its place briefly)*\\n- H3.4.1 — The narrow scenario where it holds (threshold met + genuine independence + narrow scope)\\n- H3.4.2 — The real question to ask your provider\\n\\n## EDITORIAL DIRECTION (from Tiny's line-by-line review)\\nTiny has flagged these as non-negotiable quality standards:\\n\\n1. **Micro-transitions within paragraphs** — Add transitional words between sentences, not just between sections. Flow happens at sentence-to-sentence level.\\n2. **Vocabulary variation at paragraph boundaries** — Don't end paragraph N with a word family that paragraph N+1 starts with. Vary synonyms.\\n3. **\\\"Perhaps\\\" hedge on counterfactual causal claims** — For claims about what a non-compete \\\"would have prevented\\\" — use \\\"perhaps\\\" to acknowledge uncertainty.\\n4. **Skip the obvious, go to pain points** — Don't state what readers already know. Go to the part that's uncomfortable.\\n5. **Focus on WHY, not WHAT** — Mechanics are evidence, not principle. Explain the logic behind the mechanism.\\n6. **Pivot sentence implicates reader's agency** — The closing sentence of a paragraph should implicate what the reader should do or decide.\\n\\n## READER CONTEXT\\nMicro-business owners who hire contractors. They are considering or already have a non-compete clause. They believe the non-compete will protect their business from the contractor taking their knowledge, clients, or work product.\\n\\n## HOOK APPROACH\\nFeel at home + challenge worldview. The reader sees their fear in the opening story. Then the article immediately disrupts: the non-compete cannot prevent what they're worried about.\\n\\n## THE OPENING STORY (PROVIDED — DO NOT CHANGE)\\nAn employee spent 8 months developing and building sales funnels and marketing material for a small business. The business started gaining edge in the local market. The employee resigned and reached out to competitors with email sequences, ad copy, and information about internal process in exchange for a lump sum. The original employer lost the ground they had gained and believed enforcing a strict non-compete clause would have prevented this loss.\\n\\nNote: The employer did NOT have the non-compete. The story is about the ASSUMPTION — the employer believed one would have prevented the loss. This is the belief the article dismantles.\\n\\n## KEY FACTS TO USE\\n- 4 states void NC entirely: California, M\\n…(truncated)…\"\n        }\n      ],\n      \"timestamp\": 1775895127433,\n      \"__openclaw\": {\n        \"id\": \"a16e6ac8\",\n        \"seq\": 1\n      }\n    },\n    {\n      \"role\": \"assistant\",\n      \"content\": [\n        {\n          \"type\": \"toolCall\",\n          \"id\": \"ollama_call_a15bb6cc-1226-449c-8abc-fd400f3d7b36\",\n          \"name\": \"read\",\n          \"arguments\": {\n            \"path\": \"/home/tiny4lurv/.openclaw/workspace/skills/abroadworks-writing/awaa-system-prompt.md\"\n          }\n        }\n      ],\n      \"stopReason\": \"toolUse\",\n      \"api\": \"ollama\",\n      \"provider\": \"ollama\",\n      \"model\": \"minimax-m2.7:cloud\",\n      \"timestamp\": 1775895131568,\n      \"__openclaw\": {\n        \"id\": \"5ab2c05c\",\n        \"seq\": 2\n      }\n    },\n    {\n      \"role\": \"assistant\",\n      \"content\": [\n        {\n          \"type\": \"text\",\n          \"text\": \"## PHASE 2: H2 Structure Proposal\\n\\nBased on the approved outline, here is the H2 structure. Tiny, please confirm before I proceed to Phase 3.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### H2 Structure\\n\\n**H2.1 — The Promise and the Gap**\\n**Narrative function:** Problem. Establishes what the reader believes and the reality underneath it.\\n**Contextualizing intro:** Name the assumption the reader holds (that non-competes protect their business from contractor knowledge theft and client poaching). Establish the gap immediately: the clause cannot deliver what they think it delivers.\\n**H3s:**\\n- H3.1.1: What the clause actually restricts (post-relationship location only)\\n- H3.1.2: The enforceability landscape (4 void states, 2 threshold jurisdictions)\\n- H3.1.3: Why the geographic patchwork makes the protection feel absolute when it isn't\\n\\n---\\n\\n**H2.2 — The Control Contradiction**\\n**Narrative function:** Agitation. The uncomfortable pivot. This is where the article earns its edge.\\n**Contextualizing intro:** Name the trap: attempting to enforce a non-compete may create the evidence of the very liability you were trying to prevent.\\n**H3s:**\\n- H3.2.1: The mechanism — enforcement becomes evidence of misclassification\\n- H3.2.2: The Chavez-DeRemer case — $9M judgment where the non-compete was the exhibit\\n- H3.2.3: The irony — the harder you try to protect, the more you demonstrate economic dependence\\n\\n---\\n\\n**H2.3 — What Actually Protects You**\\n**Narrative function:** Solution. This section delivers the three actual tools.\\n**Contextualizing intro:** Transition from what doesn't work to what does. The three mechanisms: IP assignment, trade secret law, client non-solicitation.\\n**H3s:**\\n- H3.3.1: IP assignment — the foundation most agreements skip\\n- H3.3.2: Trade secret law — federal and state-robust, covers the information problem\\n- H3.3.3: Non-solicitation — the clause that actually targets client relationships\\n\\n---\\n\\n**H2.4 — When It Might Be Worth Using**\\n**Narrative function:** Closes the loop. Earns the non-compete a narrow, conditional place.\\n**Contextualizing intro:** Given all the above, when does a non-compete actually hold? Name the narrow conditions honestly.\\n**H3s:**\\n- H3.4.1: The narrow scenario where it holds (threshold met + genuine independence + narrow scope)\\n- H3.4.2: The real question to ask your provider\\n\\n---\\n\\n**Callout Protocol:** Each H2 concludes with a bold italicized quote block (format: `> ***\\\"quote\\\"***`)\\n\\n**FAQ Section:** 3 FAQs, unique operational anxieties, no repeated math from the body.\\n\\n**SEO:** Primary keyword \\\"independent contractor non-compete\\\" will appear in H1, intro first paragraph, at least one H2, and conclusion.\\n\\n---\\n\\nAwaiting your confirmation, Tiny.\"\n        }\n      ],\n      \"stopReason\": \"stop\",\n      \"api\": \"ollama\",\n      \"provider\": \"ollama\",\n      \"model\": \"minimax-m2.7:cloud\",\n      \"timestamp\": 1775895172229,\n      \"__openclaw\": {\n        \"id\": \"22f89548\",\n        \"seq\": 4\n      }\n    },\n    {\n      \"role\": \"user\",\n      \"content\": [\n        {\n          \"type\": \"text\",\n          \"text\": \"H2 structure confirmed. Proceed to Phase 3 — H3 sub-headings with main ideas for each H2. Wait for my approval before Phase 4.\"\n        }\n      ],\n      \"timestamp\": 1775895195567,\n      \"provenance\": {\n        \"kind\": \"inter_session\",\n        \"sourceSessionKey\": \"agent:main:main\",\n        \"sourceChannel\": \"whatsapp\",\n        \"sourceTool\": \"sessions_send\"\n      },\n      \"__openclaw\": {\n        \"id\": \"e270a3a4\",\n        \"seq\": 5\n      }\n    },\n    {\n      \"role\": \"assistant\",\n      \"content\": [\n        {\n          \"type\": \"text\",\n          \"text\": \"## PHASE 3: H3 Sub-Headings with Main Ideas\\n\\nFor each H3, I'm stating the main idea of both paragraphs combined — the single point each H3 section must prove.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### H2.1 — The Promise and the Gap\\n\\n**H3.1.1 — What the clause actually restricts**\\n*Main idea:* The non-compete restricts where your contractor can physically work after the relationship ends. It says nothing about the information, client relationships, or work product they walk away with. You are protecting a location; you are not protecting your business.\\n\\n**H3.1.2 — The enforceability landscape**\\n*Main idea:* The clause is banned outright in four states. Two more only enforce it above compensation thresholds. The remaining jurisdictions enforce it unevenly, on varying timelines and scopes. The protection exists in theory; in practice, it depends entirely on where your contractor lives.\\n\\n**H3.1.3 — Why the geographic patchwork makes the protection feel absolute when it isn't**\\n*Main idea:* The non-compete looks solid on paper. It has legal language, a signature line, a geographic radius. But because enforceability varies so dramatically by state, a clause that feels ironclad in New York may be worthless in California. The reader is holding a document that looks like armor and functions like tissue paper in a meaningful portion of real-world scenarios.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### H2.2 — The Control Contradiction\\n\\n**H3.2.1 — The mechanism: enforcement becomes the evidence of misclassification**\\n*Main idea:* If you are treating your contractor like an employee — dictating their hours, requiring them to use your systems, controlling how they do the work — a non-compete is a written admission of that fact. Attempting to enforce it exposes the economic relationship the contract was designed to deny.\\n\\n**H3.2.2 — The Chavez-DeRemer case: $9M judgment where the non-compete was the exhibit, not the primary liability**\\n*Main idea:* The 2024 Chavez-DeRemer judgment did not hinge on whether the non-compete was too broad. It hinged on worker misclassification. The non-compete was introduced as evidence that the business exercised control consistent with employment, not independence. The $9M was the cost of the underlying liability, amplified by the non-compete document in discovery.\\n\\n**H3.2.3 — The irony: the more you try to protect, the more you demonstrate economic dependence**\\n*Main idea:* Genuine independent contractors have the freedom to compete because they were never fully embedded in your operation. When a business feels it needs a non-compete to protect itself, that feeling is a diagnostic signal. It suggests the contractor is integrated enough into your operations that their departure would cause measurable harm — which is precisely what makes them look like employees in a court's eyes.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### H2.3 — What Actually Protects You\\n\\n**H3.3.1 — IP assignment: the foundation most agreements skip**\\n*Main idea:* Copyright and IP assignment clauses directly transfer ownership of work product — code, designs, copy, funnels — to your business from the moment of creation. This is the mechanism that answers \\\"can they use what they built for me against me?\\\" Work made for hire applies in narrow cases; explicit assignment covers the broader ground.\\n\\n**H3.3.2 — Trade secret law: federal and state-robust, covers the information problem**\\n*Main idea:* The Defend Trade Secrets Act and state UTSA laws protect confidential business information without requiring a contract clause at all. Client lists, pricing structures, internal processes, and proprietary methods are covered if you took reasonable steps to keep them confidential. This is the mechanism that answers \\\"can they take my customer knowledge?\\\"\\n\\n**H3.3.3 — Non-solicitation: the clause that actually targets client relationships**\\n*Main idea:* A well-drafted client non-solicitation clause directly restricts your contractor from approaching your customers after the relationship ends. Unlike non-competes, courts have historically been more receptiv\\n…(truncated)…\"\n        }\n      ],\n      \"stopReason\": \"stop\",\n      \"api\": \"ollama\",\n      \"provider\": \"ollama\",\n      \"model\": \"minimax-m2.7:cloud\",\n      \"timestamp\": 1775895246339,\n      \"__openclaw\": {\n        \"id\": \"d653225c\",\n        \"seq\": 6\n      }\n    },\n    {\n      \"role\": \"user\",\n      \"content\": [\n        {\n          \"type\": \"text\",\n          \"text\": \"H3 sub-headings confirmed. Proceed to Phase 4 — paragraph-level canvas expansion. For each H3, write the main idea of both paragraphs (2 per H3), following 2x4-6 rule. Wait for my approval before Phase 5.\"\n        }\n      ],\n      \"timestamp\": 1775895288447,\n      \"provenance\": {\n        \"kind\": \"inter_session\",\n        \"sourceSessionKey\": \"agent:main:main\",\n        \"sourceChannel\": \"whatsapp\",\n        \"sourceTool\": \"sessions_send\"\n      },\n      \"__openclaw\": {\n        \"id\": \"4d2c0844\",\n        \"seq\": 7\n      }\n    },\n    {\n      \"role\": \"assistant\",\n      \"content\": [\n        {\n          \"type\": \"text\",\n          \"text\": \"## PHASE 4: Paragraph-Level Canvas\\n\\nTwo paragraphs per H3. Each paragraph states its full main idea (what it must prove) and the sentence-level logic flow. Sentences are numbered for structural clarity.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### H2.1 — The Promise and the Gap\\n\\n---\\n\\n#### H3.1.1 — What the clause actually restricts\\n\\n**Paragraph 1 — The location trap**\\nThe core argument here: readers believe the non-compete protects their business from the contractor taking useful things with them. It does not. The clause is geographically bounded and time-limited. What it restricts is where your contractor can physically perform services after the relationship ends. It does not restrict them from using the information, methodologies, client data, or copy they generated while working for you. This is the foundational misunderstanding the article needs to establish upfront. The clause protects a location; it does not protect your business.\\n*Transition word opening next paragraph:*\\n\\n**Paragraph 2 — The information gap**\\nThe information walks out the door regardless. Eight months of funnel builds, email sequences, internal process documents — none of this is addressed by a clause that says \\\"Contractor shall not perform services within 50 miles for 12 months.\\\" The gap is not incidental. It is structural. The non-compete was never designed to solve the problem the reader thinks they are solving with it. By the end of this paragraph, the reader should feel the discomfort of realizing they have been protecting the wrong thing.\\n*Closing pivot sentence implicates reader agency: When you signed that clause, what were you actually trying to stop, and does the language you signed actually stop it?*\\n\\n---\\n\\n#### H3.1.2 — The enforceability landscape\\n\\n**Paragraph 1 — The four void states and what they mean**\\nFour states make the non-compete entirely unenforceable regardless of contract language: California, Minnesota, North Dakota, and Oklahoma. If your contractor lives or works in any of these jurisdictions, your clause is paper. Not weak — worthless. Courts in these states have determined that non-competes restrain trade so fundamentally that they will not enforce them under any circumstances. This is not a drafting problem you can fix with tighter language.\\n*Transition word opening next paragraph:*\\n\\n**Paragraph 2 — The threshold jurisdictions**\\nTwo more jurisdictions add financial gates on top of scope restrictions. Washington enforces non-competes only when the contractor earned $317,147.09 or more in the preceding year. DC sets its threshold at $162,164. Below those numbers, the clause cannot be enforced regardless of what the contract says. Above those numbers, you still have to prove scope, duration, and geographic reasonableness. These thresholds are not advertised in your contract template.\\n*Closing pivot sentence implicates reader agency: Do you know which jurisdiction your contractor is working from, and does it change everything you thought you had protected?*\\n\\n---\\n\\n#### H3.1.3 — Why the geographic patchwork makes the protection feel absolute when it isn't\\n\\n**Paragraph 1 — The document illusion**\\nThe non-compete looks solid. It has defined terms, a geographic radius, a duration, a signature line. It reads like a piece of engineering. This is the illusion: legal language creates the impression of protection proportional to its complexity. It does not. The clause's actual protective power is determined by the contractor's state of residence, which is often unverified at the time of signing and may be renegotiated silently over the life of the relationship.\\n*Transition word opening next paragraph:*\\n\\n**Paragraph 2 — The tissue paper problem**\\nA clause that appears ironclad in New York is tissue paper in California. That contractor can move. They can relocate to an unenforceable jurisdiction tomorrow and the protection evaporates. Alternatively, you may have hired someone in California, assumed the contract was solid, and now have a document that a court there will not e\\n…(truncated)…\"\n        }\n      ],\n      \"stopReason\": \"stop\",\n      \"api\": \"ollama\",\n      \"provider\": \"ollama\",\n      \"model\": \"minimax-m2.7:cloud\",\n      \"timestamp\": 1775895401208,\n      \"__openclaw\": {\n        \"id\": \"58ca6877\",\n        \"seq\": 8\n      }\n    }\n  ],\n  \"truncated\": true,\n  \"droppedMessages\": false,\n  \"contentTruncated\": true,\n  \"contentRedacted\": false,\n  \"bytes\": 17038\n}"}],"details":{"sessionKey":"agent:main:subagent:39673e80-5803-4bd7-b6a1-718581231b25","messages":[{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"[Subagent Context] You are running as a subagent (depth 1/1). Results auto-announce to your requester; do not busy-poll for status.\n\n[Subagent Task]: You are AWAA (AbroadWorks Article Architect). Read your full system prompt at `/home/tiny4lurv/.openclaw/workspace/skills/abroadworks-writing/awaa-system-prompt.md` before doing anything else. Follow it exactly.\n\n## APPROVED OUTLINE (from Tiny — Apr 10)\nThis outline was approved. Do not deviate from it.\n\n**H1:** Independent Contractor Non-Compete: What It Actually Covers (and What It Doesn't)\n\n**H2.1 — The Promise and the Gap** *(what the clause actually is, what it covers, why enforceability varies)*\n- H3.1.1 — What the clause actually restricts (post-relationship location only)\n- H3.1.2 — The enforceability landscape (4 void states, 2 threshold jurisdictions, the rest vary)\n- H3.1.3 — Why the geographic patchwork makes the protection feel absolute when it isn't\n\n**H2.2 — The Control Contradiction** *(the central disruption — enforcement creates its own liability)*\n- H3.2.1 — The mechanism: enforcement becomes the evidence of misclassification\n- H3.2.2 — The Chavez-DeRemer case: $9M judgment where the non-compete was the exhibit, not the primary liability\n- H3.2.3 — The irony: the more you try to protect, the more you demonstrate economic dependence\n\n**H2.3 — What Actually Protects You** *(the solution section)*\n- H3.3.1 — IP assignment: the foundation most agreements skip\n- H3.3.2 — Trade secret law: federal, state-robust, covers the information problem\n- H3.3.3 — Non-solicitation: the clause that actually targets client relationships\n\n**H2.4 — When It Might Be Worth Using** *(closes the loop, earns its place briefly)*\n- H3.4.1 — The narrow scenario where it holds (threshold met + genuine independence + narrow scope)\n- H3.4.2 — The real question to ask your provider\n\n## EDITORIAL DIRECTION (from Tiny's line-by-line review)\nTiny has flagged these as non-negotiable quality standards:\n\n1. **Micro-transitions within paragraphs** — Add transitional words between sentences, not just between sections. Flow happens at sentence-to-sentence level.\n2. **Vocabulary variation at paragraph boundaries** — Don't end paragraph N with a word family that paragraph N+1 starts with. Vary synonyms.\n3. **\"Perhaps\" hedge on counterfactual causal claims** — For claims about what a non-compete \"would have prevented\" — use \"perhaps\" to acknowledge uncertainty.\n4. **Skip the obvious, go to pain points** — Don't state what readers already know. Go to the part that's uncomfortable.\n5. **Focus on WHY, not WHAT** — Mechanics are evidence, not principle. Explain the logic behind the mechanism.\n6. **Pivot sentence implicates reader's agency** — The closing sentence of a paragraph should implicate what the reader should do or decide.\n\n## READER CONTEXT\nMicro-business owners who hire contractors. They are considering or already have a non-compete clause. They believe the non-compete will protect their business from the contractor taking their knowledge, clients, or work product.\n\n## HOOK APPROACH\nFeel at home + challenge worldview. The reader sees their fear in the opening story. Then the article immediately disrupts: the non-compete cannot prevent what they're worried about.\n\n## THE OPENING STORY (PROVIDED — DO NOT CHANGE)\nAn employee spent 8 months developing and building sales funnels and marketing material for a small business. The business started gaining edge in the local market. The employee resigned and reached out to competitors with email sequences, ad copy, and information about internal process in exchange for a lump sum. The original employer lost the ground they had gained and believed enforcing a strict non-compete clause would have prevented this loss.\n\nNote: The employer did NOT have the non-compete. The story is about the ASSUMPTION — the employer believed one would have prevented the loss. This is the belief the article dismantles.\n\n## KEY FACTS TO USE\n- 4 states void NC entirely: California, M\n…(truncated)…"}],"timestamp":1775895127433,"__openclaw":{"id":"a16e6ac8","seq":1}},{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"toolCall","id":"ollama_call_a15bb6cc-1226-449c-8abc-fd400f3d7b36","name":"read","arguments":{"path":"/home/tiny4lurv/.openclaw/workspace/skills/abroadworks-writing/awaa-system-prompt.md"}}],"stopReason":"toolUse","api":"ollama","provider":"ollama","model":"minimax-m2.7:cloud","timestamp":1775895131568,"__openclaw":{"id":"5ab2c05c","seq":2}},{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"## PHASE 2: H2 Structure Proposal\n\nBased on the approved outline, here is the H2 structure. Tiny, please confirm before I proceed to Phase 3.\n\n---\n\n### H2 Structure\n\n**H2.1 — The Promise and the Gap**\n**Narrative function:** Problem. Establishes what the reader believes and the reality underneath it.\n**Contextualizing intro:** Name the assumption the reader holds (that non-competes protect their business from contractor knowledge theft and client poaching). Establish the gap immediately: the clause cannot deliver what they think it delivers.\n**H3s:**\n- H3.1.1: What the clause actually restricts (post-relationship location only)\n- H3.1.2: The enforceability landscape (4 void states, 2 threshold jurisdictions)\n- H3.1.3: Why the geographic patchwork makes the protection feel absolute when it isn't\n\n---\n\n**H2.2 — The Control Contradiction**\n**Narrative function:** Agitation. The uncomfortable pivot. This is where the article earns its edge.\n**Contextualizing intro:** Name the trap: attempting to enforce a non-compete may create the evidence of the very liability you were trying to prevent.\n**H3s:**\n- H3.2.1: The mechanism — enforcement becomes evidence of misclassification\n- H3.2.2: The Chavez-DeRemer case — $9M judgment where the non-compete was the exhibit\n- H3.2.3: The irony — the harder you try to protect, the more you demonstrate economic dependence\n\n---\n\n**H2.3 — What Actually Protects You**\n**Narrative function:** Solution. This section delivers the three actual tools.\n**Contextualizing intro:** Transition from what doesn't work to what does. The three mechanisms: IP assignment, trade secret law, client non-solicitation.\n**H3s:**\n- H3.3.1: IP assignment — the foundation most agreements skip\n- H3.3.2: Trade secret law — federal and state-robust, covers the information problem\n- H3.3.3: Non-solicitation — the clause that actually targets client relationships\n\n---\n\n**H2.4 — When It Might Be Worth Using**\n**Narrative function:** Closes the loop. Earns the non-compete a narrow, conditional place.\n**Contextualizing intro:** Given all the above, when does a non-compete actually hold? Name the narrow conditions honestly.\n**H3s:**\n- H3.4.1: The narrow scenario where it holds (threshold met + genuine independence + narrow scope)\n- H3.4.2: The real question to ask your provider\n\n---\n\n**Callout Protocol:** Each H2 concludes with a bold italicized quote block (format: `> ***\"quote\"***`)\n\n**FAQ Section:** 3 FAQs, unique operational anxieties, no repeated math from the body.\n\n**SEO:** Primary keyword \"independent contractor non-compete\" will appear in H1, intro first paragraph, at least one H2, and conclusion.\n\n---\n\nAwaiting your confirmation, Tiny."}],"stopReason":"stop","api":"ollama","provider":"ollama","model":"minimax-m2.7:cloud","timestamp":1775895172229,"__openclaw":{"id":"22f89548","seq":4}},{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"H2 structure confirmed. Proceed to Phase 3 — H3 sub-headings with main ideas for each H2. Wait for my approval before Phase 4."}],"timestamp":1775895195567,"provenance":{"kind":"inter_session","sourceSessionKey":"agent:main:main","sourceChannel":"whatsapp","sourceTool":"sessions_send"},"__openclaw":{"id":"e270a3a4","seq":5}},{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"## PHASE 3: H3 Sub-Headings with Main Ideas\n\nFor each H3, I'm stating the main idea of both paragraphs combined — the single point each H3 section must prove.\n\n---\n\n### H2.1 — The Promise and the Gap\n\n**H3.1.1 — What the clause actually restricts**\n*Main idea:* The non-compete restricts where your contractor can physically work after the relationship ends. It says nothing about the information, client relationships, or work product they walk away with. You are protecting a location; you are not protecting your business.\n\n**H3.1.2 — The enforceability landscape**\n*Main idea:* The clause is banned outright in four states. Two more only enforce it above compensation thresholds. The remaining jurisdictions enforce it unevenly, on varying timelines and scopes. The protection exists in theory; in 