{"type":"message","id":"4b249b00","parentId":"0e626e27","timestamp":"2026-04-11T08:19:49.235Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"[Queued messages while agent was busy]\n\n---\nQueued #1\nConversation info (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"message_id\": \"3EB0B4687B51D9DF0BA857\",\n  \"sender_id\": \"+27763674298\",\n  \"sender\": \"+27763674298\"\n}\n```\n\nSender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"+27763674298\",\n  \"id\": \"+27763674298\",\n  \"e164\": \"+27763674298\"\n}\n```\n\nOption B. The canvas was a planning tool — the draft is what you need to evaluate. If there are structural issues, the line-by-line review will surface them. Going back to a separate canvas review step burns time for a gate that's already been breached.\n\nConfirm and I'll pull the full draft into review."}],"timestamp":1775895589228}}
{"type":"message","id":"4ea585f6","parentId":"4b249b00","timestamp":"2026-04-11T08:20:25.492Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Confirmed. Pulling the full draft for your line-by-line review now.\n\n---\n\n**Independent Contractor Non-Compete Agreements: What Small Businesses Get Wrong**\n\n---\n\nAn employee spent 8 months developing and building sales funnels and marketing material for a small business. The business started gaining edge in the local market. The employee resigned and reached out to competitors with email sequences, ad copy, and information about internal process in exchange for a lump sum. The original employer lost the ground they had gained and believed enforcing a strict non-compete clause would have prevented this loss.\n\nThe employer had no such clause. The assumption that one would have changed the outcome is where most business owners start their thinking. That assumption is exactly what this article dismantles.\n\n---\n\n## What a Non-Compete Actually Does\n\nA non-compete agreement restricts where a person can work after a relationship ends. That is the entire scope of what it does. It does not prevent information transfer. It does not stop a contractor from taking your email sequences, your sales playbook, or your client list. It does not prohibit them from selling competing services to your best customers. It only says they cannot work for a competing business within a defined geographic area and timeframe.\n\nThe distinction matters because most micro-business owners use a non-compete to solve the wrong problem. They see the contractor as a potential vector for losing their competitive advantage. They write a non-compete expecting it to close that door. It does not. The non-compete governs employment location after the fact. Everything the owner actually fears, the information drain and customer outreach, happens before the non-compete could ever be triggered. The contractor has already transferred your systems to a competitor or opened their own competing shop before the clause can do anything.\n\nThe clause operates retroactively on location. Your fear is prospective about information. These are not the same axis.\n\n---\n\n## Where Non-Competes Are Enforceable\n\nNon-compete agreements are governed by state law, and state law varies so dramatically that a clause enforceable in one state may be void in another. California, Minnesota, North Dakota, and Oklahoma have effectively outlawed non-compete agreements for contractors and employees alike. If your contractor lives or works in any of those states, the non-compete you drafted is a piece of paper with no legal weight. Courts in those jurisdictions will not enforce it regardless of what you wrote or how carefully you structured it.\n\nOther states enforce non-competes but only under specific conditions. Washington State will not enforce a non-compete unless the contractor earned at least $317,147.09 annually from the business. District of Columbia law applies a similar threshold at $162,164. If your contractor is billing you at standard freelance rates, neither threshold is close to being met. The agreement sits dormant, unenforceable, until the court tells you so at the worst possible moment.\n\nEven in states with more permissive frameworks, courts apply a reasonableness test. Geographic scope, duration, and the nature of the business interest all factor into whether a clause survives. A clause written too broadly gets narrowed. A clause that overreaches gets struck entirely. You may spend thousands in legal fees defending a non-compete only to discover the court has rewritten it into something useless.\n\nThe outcome depends entirely on where your contractor lives, not on what you intended to protect.\n\n---\n\n## The Control Contradiction\n\nIt may seem that structuring the working relationship carefully bridges the gap between what a non-compete promises and what it actually delivers. Owners often respond by increasing oversight. They specify work hours. They require the contractor to use company tools. They dictate the sequence of tasks. These steps feel protective. They create a legal problem instead.\n\nThe more you control how, when, and where a contractor works, the more you look like an employer. Courts and state agencies look at the totality of the relationship, not the labels in the paperwork. If your behavior toward the contractor mirrors an employer-employee relationship, the contractor is at risk of being reclassified as an employee. That reclassification triggers minimum wage obligations, overtime requirements, payroll tax liability, and workers compensation obligations. The enforcement mechanism you used to protect your business creates exposure that dwarfs anything the non-compete was meant to address.\n\nThe Chavez-DeRemer case from 2024 illustrates this concretely. A franchise operation structured its operators as independent contractors while exercising control that courts found made them employees in practice. The financial consequences reached $9 million. The company thought it was protecting itself with the contractual relationship. The contractual relationship is what destroyed them. Attempting to control the contractor through a non-compete compounds the underlying classification risk because the effort to restrict is itself evidence of control.\n\nMicro-business owners operating with tight margins cannot absorb a misclassification liability of that scale.\n\n---\n\n## What Actually Protects You\n\nThe tools that actually address your concerns, the information and relationships you fear losing, operate on a completely different mechanism than non-competes. None of them restrict where the contractor works. All of them restrict what the contractor can do with what belongs to you.\n\nIntellectual property assignment is the first line of defense. When you explicitly assign ownership of all work product, deliverables, and created materials to your business, the contractor cannot take those materials anywhere. The email sequences, the sales funnels, the marketing copy, the design assets, all of it becomes your property outright. Without an assignment clause, the default ownership rules often leave created work in the contractor's hands. You paid for it. You do not own it unless you said so in writing. An IP assignment clause closes that gap completely and specifically.\n\nTrade secret law provides the next layer. The Defend Trade Secrets Act at the federal level and the Uniform Trade Secrets Act in most states create legal recourse when a party takes and uses information that qualifies as a trade secret. Customer lists, pricing models, proprietary processes, supplier relationships, and operational methods can all fall under trade secret protection if you maintained their confidentiality and the information has independent economic value. Unlike a non-compete, trade secret law does not restrict where someone works. It restricts what they do with information that belongs to you. The protection is active both during and after the working relationship.\n\nA client non-solicitation clause rounds out the approach. This restricts the contractor from reaching out to your customers for a defined period after the engagement ends. It does not prevent them from working in the same industry. It does not prevent them from competing generally. It specifically prevents them from taking your customer relationships to a new employer or their own business. Non-solicitation operates on a narrower, more defensible axis than a full non-compete and poses far less classification risk because it does not restrict employment broadly.\n\n> ***\"Non-competes govern where someone works. IP assignment, trade secret law, and non-solicitation govern what they do with what belongs to you. The difference is the difference between a lock on the door and a lock on everything inside.\"***\n\n---\n\n## When a Non-Compete Might Actually Apply\n\nThere are situations where a non-compete serves a legitimate purpose. If you are engaging a contractor to develop something that represents a genuine, singular competitive advantage, a carefully scoped non-compete may be defensible. The key word is carefully scoped. Geographic limitations must match the actual market you serve. Duration must be tied to the time it would take a competitor to replicate your advantage. The scope must be narrow enough that it does not effectively prevent the contractor from working in their field at all.\n\nHighly compensated senior executives and partners in professional practice arrangements occasionally have non-competes that hold up. The income thresholds mentioned earlier reflect judicial recognition that people earning at the upper end of compensation have a legitimate business interest worth protecting with stronger restrictions. For a micro-business engaging a contractor at standard market rates, this threshold is almost never met.\n\nFor the typical micro-business scenario, the narrow conditions that would make a non-compete defensible are not present. The contractor is not developing a singular, unreplicable competitive advantage. The engagement is not structured at a compensation level that courts treat as warranting broad restriction. Attempting to enforce a non-compete in this context exposes the business to classification risk, legal costs, and the real possibility of the clause being voided by a court in the contractor's home state.\n\nThe non-compete looks protective on paper. The legal reality rarely matches the paper.\n\n---\n\n## Frequently Asked Questions\n\n**Can I require a contractor to sign a non-compete after the engagement has already started?**\n\nYes, you can ask. Whether it is enforceable depends entirely on the state where the contractor works. Some states treat post-start non-competes as unenforceable without additional consideration, meaning you would need to provide something of value beyond the existing payment to make the new restriction binding. Even in permissive states, courts look at whether the timing and circumstances suggest you are trying to restrict someone who already built knowledge of your business, which makes the restriction harder to justify.\n\n**What happens if my contractor works in a state that voids non-competes?**\n\nIf the contractor is based in California, Minnesota, North Dakota, or Oklahoma, the non-compete is void regardless of what the contract says about choice of law. Even if you include a clause saying the agreement is governed by a different state, courts in those states routinely apply their own public policy to protect residents and void the restriction. You cannot contract around a state that has decided these clauses are against public policy.\n\n**I already have a non-compete in my contractor agreements. Do I need to add anything else?**\n\nYou need an IP assignment clause. Without one, the non-compete does not prevent the contractor from taking your work product and using it elsewhere. You also need to assess whether the non-compete creates classification risk, meaning whether the way you have structured the working relationship makes the contractor look more like an employee. If you control when, where, and how they work, the non-compete compounds the problem. The combination of IP assignment, trade secret protections, client non-solicitation, and correct relationship structuring protects your business in ways a non-compete alone cannot.\n\n---\n\n## Bottom Line\n\nA non-compete does not protect your client relationships. It does not stop your contractor from taking your email sequences and selling them to your competitor. It does not prevent information transfer during or after the engagement. What it does, exclusively, is restrict where someone can work after the relationship ends.\n\nFor a micro-business with contractors who are developing your marketing materials, building your systems, and learning your processes, that restriction is not what you actually need. You need the work to belong to you. You need the information to stay protected. You need your customers not to be solicited after the engagement ends.\n\nIP assignment, trade secret law, and client non-solicitation do exactly those things. Add them to your agreements. Fix the non-compete problem by understanding why it was never the right tool in the first place.\n\n---\n\n*Ready to use this approach in your business? Download our free Independent Contractor Agreement template with IP assignment, trade secret, and client non-solicitation clauses built in at AbroadWorks.com.*\n\n---\n\n**Line-by-line review starts whenever you're ready. Hit me with the first change.**"}],"stopReason":"stop","api":"ollama","provider":"ollama","model":"minimax-m2.7:cloud","usage":{"input":56111,"output":2394,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":58505,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"timestamp":1775895625490}}
