are situations where a non-compete serves a legitimate purpose. If you are engaging a contractor to develop something that represents a genuine, singular competitive advantage, a carefully scoped non-compete may be defensible. The key word is carefully scoped. Geographic limitations must match the actual market you serve. Duration must be tied to the time it would take a competitor to replicate your advantage. The scope must be narrow enough that it does not effectively prevent the contractor from working in their field at all.\n\nHighly compensated senior executives and partners in professional practice arrangements occasionally have non-competes that hold up. The income thresholds mentioned earlier reflect judicial recognition that people earning at the upper end of compensation have a legitimate business interest worth protecting with stronger restrictions. For a micro-business engaging a contractor at standard market rates, this threshold is almost never met.\n\nFor the typical micro-business scenario, the narrow conditions that would make a non-compete defensible are not present. The contractor is not developing a singular, unreplicable competitive advantage. The engagement is not structured at a compensation level that courts treat as warranting broad restriction. Attempting to enforce a non-compete in this context exposes the business to classification risk, legal costs, and the real possibility of the clause being voided by a court in the contractor's home state.\n\nThe non-compete looks protective on paper. The legal reality rarely matches the paper.\n\n---\n\n## Frequently Asked Questions\n\n**Can I require a contractor to sign a non-compete after the engagement has already started?**\n\nYes, you can ask. Whether it is enforceable depends entirely on the state where the contractor works. Some states treat post-start non-competes as unenforceable without additional consideration, meaning you would need to provide something of value beyond the existing payment to make the new restriction binding. Even in permissive states, courts look at whether the timing and circumstances suggest you are trying to restrict someone who already built knowledge of your business, which makes the restriction harder to justify.\n\n**What happens if my contractor works in a state that voids non-competes?**\n\nIf the contractor is based in California, Minnesota, North Dakota, or Oklahoma, the non-compete is void regardless of what the contract says about choice of law. Even if you include a clause saying the agreement is governed by a different state, courts in those states routinely apply their own public policy to protect residents and void the restriction. You cannot contract around a state that has decided these clauses are against public policy.\n\n**I already have a non-compete in my contractor agreements. Do I need to add anything else?**\n\nYou need an IP assignment clause. Without one, the non-compete does not prevent the contractor from taking your work product and using it elsewhere. You also need to assess whether the non-compete creates classification risk, meaning whether the way you have structured the working relationship makes the contractor look more like an employee. If you control when, where, and how they work, the non-compete compounds the problem. The combination of IP assignment, trade secret protections, client non-solicitation, and correct relationship structuring protects your business in ways a non-compete alone cannot.\n\n---\n\n## Bottom Line\n\nA non-compete does not protect your client relationships. It does not stop your contractor from taking your email sequences and selling them to your competitor. It does not prevent information transfer during or after the engagement. What it does, exclusively, is restrict where someone can work after the relationship ends.\n\nFor a micro-business with contractors who are developing your marketing materials, building your systems, and learning your processes, that restriction is not what you actually need. You need the work to belong to you. You need the information to stay protected. You need your customers not to be solicited after the engagement ends.\n\nIP assignment, trade secret law, and client non-solicitation do exactly those things. Add them to your agreements. Fix the non-compete problem by understanding why it was never the right tool in the first place.\n\n---\n\n*Ready to use this approach in your business? Download our free Independent Contractor Agreement template with IP assignment, trade secret, and client non-solicitation clauses built in at AbroadWorks.com.*\n\n---\n\n**Line-by-line review starts whenever you're ready. Hit me with the first change.**"}],"api":"openai-responses","provider":"openclaw","model":"delivery-mirror","usage":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":0,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1775895625654}}
