{"type":"message","id":"b1b94c9b","parentId":"7b5e5728","timestamp":"2026-04-11T08:36:34.447Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"ollama_call_14eff4b7-33df-4d6a-b439-cc36dcbeee16","toolName":"subagents","content":[{"type":"text","text":"{\n  \"status\": \"done\",\n  \"action\": \"kill\",\n  \"target\": \"agent:main:subagent:39673e80-5803-4bd7-b6a1-718581231b25\",\n  \"runId\": \"abedb0aa-c447-4e06-8f9b-3700ebdd8545\",\n  \"sessionKey\": \"agent:main:subagent:39673e80-5803-4bd7-b6a1-718581231b25\",\n  \"label\": \"You are AWAA (AbroadWorks Article Architect). Read your full system prompt at `/home/tiny4lurv/.openclaw/workspace/skills/abroadworks-writing/awaa-system-prompt.md` before doing anything else. Follow it exactly.\\n\\n## APPROVED OUTLINE (from Tiny — Apr 10)\\nThis outline was approved. Do not deviate from it.\\n\\n**H1:** Independent Contractor Non-Compete: What It Actually Covers (and What It Doesn't)\\n\\n**H2.1 — The Promise and the Gap** *(what the clause actually is, what it covers, why enforceability varies)*\\n- H3.1.1 — What the clause actually restricts (post-relationship location only)\\n- H3.1.2 — The enforceability landscape (4 void states, 2 threshold jurisdictions, the rest vary)\\n- H3.1.3 — Why the geographic patchwork makes the protection feel absolute when it isn't\\n\\n**H2.2 — The Control Contradiction** *(the central disruption — enforcement creates its own liability)*\\n- H3.2.1 — The mechanism: enforcement becomes the evidence of misclassification\\n- H3.2.2 — The Chavez-DeRemer case: $9M judgment where the non-compete was the exhibit, not the primary liability\\n- H3.2.3 — The irony: the more you try to protect, the more you demonstrate economic dependence\\n\\n**H2.3 — What Actually Protects You** *(the solution section)*\\n- H3.3.1 — IP assignment: the foundation most agreements skip\\n- H3.3.2 — Trade secret law: federal, state-robust, covers the information problem\\n- H3.3.3 — Non-solicitation: the clause that actually targets client relationships\\n\\n**H2.4 — When It Might Be Worth Using** *(closes the loop, earns its place briefly)*\\n- H3.4.1 — The narrow scenario where it holds (threshold met + genuine independence + narrow scope)\\n- H3.4.2 — The real question to ask your provider\\n\\n## EDITORIAL DIRECTION (from Tiny's line-by-line review)\\nTiny has flagged these as non-negotiable quality standards:\\n\\n1. **Micro-transitions within paragraphs** — Add transitional words between sentences, not just between sections. Flow happens at sentence-to-sentence level.\\n2. **Vocabulary variation at paragraph boundaries** — Don't end paragraph N with a word family that paragraph N+1 starts with. Vary synonyms.\\n3. **\\\"Perhaps\\\" hedge on counterfactual causal claims** — For claims about what a non-compete \\\"would have prevented\\\" — use \\\"perhaps\\\" to acknowledge uncertainty.\\n4. **Skip the obvious, go to pain points** — Don't state what readers already know. Go to the part that's uncomfortable.\\n5. **Focus on WHY, not WHAT** — Mechanics are evidence, not principle. Explain the logic behind the mechanism.\\n6. **Pivot sentence implicates reader's agency** — The closing sentence of a paragraph should implicate what the reader should do or decide.\\n\\n## READER CONTEXT\\nMicro-business owners who hire contractors. They are considering or already have a non-compete clause. They believe the non-compete will protect their business from the contractor taking their knowledge, clients, or work product.\\n\\n## HOOK APPROACH\\nFeel at home + challenge worldview. The reader sees their fear in the opening story. Then the article immediately disrupts: the non-compete cannot prevent what they're worried about.\\n\\n## THE OPENING STORY (PROVIDED — DO NOT CHANGE)\\nAn employee spent 8 months developing and building sales funnels and marketing material for a small business. The business started gaining edge in the local market. The employee resigned and reached out to competitors with email sequences, ad copy, and information about internal process in exchange for a lump sum. The original employer lost the ground they had gained and believed enforcing a strict non-compete clause would have prevented this loss.\\n\\nNote: The employer did NOT have the non-compete. The story is about the ASSUMPTION — the employer believed one would have prevented the loss. This is the belief the article dismantles.\\n\\n## KEY FACTS TO USE\\n- 4 states void NC entirely: California, Minnesota, North Dakota, Oklahoma\\n- Washington threshold: $317,147.09\\n- DC threshold: $162,164\\n- Chavez-DeRemer case: $9M judgment (2024)\\n- Three actual tools: IP assignment, trade secret law (DTSA/UTSA), client non-solicitation\\n- Work Made for Hire: narrow scope\\n- Primary keyword: \\\"independent contractor non-compete\\\"\\n\\n## STRUCTURAL RULES (from system prompt — mandatory)\\n- 2x4-6 Rule: each H3 = exactly 2 paragraphs, 4-6 sentences each\\n- Bridge Protocol: every paragraph except first in a section leads with a transition word\\n- Callout Protocol: every H2 section concludes with > ***\\\"quote\\\"***\\n- H2 Intro Rule: every H2 has a contextualizing intro paragraph before first H3\\n- FAQ Section: 3 FAQs, unique operational anxieties, NO repeated math from body\\n- Meta block: Title, Meta Description, Keywords before H1\\n- SEO: primary keyword in H1, first paragraph, at least one H2, conclusion\\n\\n## VOICE\\nPlain English. Founder of 1-10 person company voice. Edgy, contrarian, urgent. No bold in body text. No em-dashes. No contractions in formal articles.\\n\\n## YOUR WORKFLOW\\nSince the outline is already approved, start at PHASE 2 (H2 structure proposal) and present it for Tiny's confirmation. Wait for approval before proceeding to Phase 3.\\n\\nPhase 2: Present the H2 structure based on the approved outline. Confirm Tiny approves before proceeding.\\nPhase 3: Propose H3 sub-headings with main ideas. Wait for approval.\\nPhase 4: Paragraph-level expansion (Canvas). Wait for approval.\\nPhase 5: Full draft. Present for evaluation.\\n\\nFollow the evaluation checklist in your system prompt before presenting any draft.\\n\\nStart now with Phase 2 — present the H2 structure for approval.\",\n  \"text\": \"You are AWAA (AbroadWorks Article Architect). Read your full system prompt at `/home/tiny4lurv/.openclaw/workspace/skills/abroadworks-writing/awaa-system-prompt.md` before doing anything else. Follow it exactly.\\n\\n## APPROVED OUTLINE (from Tiny — Apr 10)\\nThis outline was approved. Do not deviate from it.\\n\\n**H1:** Independent Contractor Non-Compete: What It Actually Covers (and What It Doesn't)\\n\\n**H2.1 — The Promise and the Gap** *(what the clause actually is, what it covers, why enforceability varies)*\\n- H3.1.1 — What the clause actually restricts (post-relationship location only)\\n- H3.1.2 — The enforceability landscape (4 void states, 2 threshold jurisdictions, the rest vary)\\n- H3.1.3 — Why the geographic patchwork makes the protection feel absolute when it isn't\\n\\n**H2.2 — The Control Contradiction** *(the central disruption — enforcement creates its own liability)*\\n- H3.2.1 — The mechanism: enforcement becomes the evidence of misclassification\\n- H3.2.2 — The Chavez-DeRemer case: $9M judgment where the non-compete was the exhibit, not the primary liability\\n- H3.2.3 — The irony: the more you try to protect, the more you demonstrate economic dependence\\n\\n**H2.3 — What Actually Protects You** *(the solution section)*\\n- H3.3.1 — IP assignment: the foundation most agreements skip\\n- H3.3.2 — Trade secret law: federal, state-robust, covers the information problem\\n- H3.3.3 — Non-solicitation: the clause that actually targets client relationships\\n\\n**H2.4 — When It Might Be Worth Using** *(closes the loop, earns its place briefly)*\\n- H3.4.1 — The narrow scenario where it holds (threshold met + genuine independence + narrow scope)\\n- H3.4.2 — The real question to ask your provider\\n\\n## EDITORIAL DIRECTION (from Tiny's line-by-line review)\\nTiny has flagged these as non-negotiable quality standards:\\n\\n1. **Micro-transitions within paragraphs** — Add transitional words between sentences, not just between sections. Flow happens at sentence-to-sentence level.\\n2. **Vocabulary variation at paragraph boundaries** — Don't end paragraph N with a word family that paragraph N+1 starts with. Vary synonyms.\\n3. **\\\"Perhaps\\\" hedge on counterfactual causal claims** — For claims about what a non-compete \\\"would have prevented\\\" — use \\\"perhaps\\\" to acknowledge uncertainty.\\n4. **Skip the obvious, go to pain points** — Don't state what readers already know. Go to the part that's uncomfortable.\\n5. **Focus on WHY, not WHAT** — Mechanics are evidence, not principle. Explain the logic behind the mechanism.\\n6. **Pivot sentence implicates reader's agency** — The closing sentence of a paragraph should implicate what the reader should do or decide.\\n\\n## READER CONTEXT\\nMicro-business owners who hire contractors. They are considering or already have a non-compete clause. They believe the non-compete will protect their business from the contractor taking their knowledge, clients, or work product.\\n\\n## HOOK APPROACH\\nFeel at home + challenge worldview. The reader sees their fear in the opening story. Then the article immediately disrupts: the non-compete cannot prevent what they're worried about.\\n\\n## THE OPENING STORY (PROVIDED — DO NOT CHANGE)\\nAn employee spent 8 months developing and building sales funnels and marketing material for a small business. The business started gaining edge in the local market. The employee resigned and reached out to competitors with email sequences, ad copy, and information about internal process in exchange for a lump sum. The original employer lost the ground they had gained and believed enforcing a strict non-compete clause would have prevented this loss.\\n\\nNote: The employer did NOT have the non-compete. The story is about the ASSUMPTION — the employer believed one would have prevented the loss. This is the belief the article dismantles.\\n\\n## KEY FACTS TO USE\\n- 4 states void NC entirely: California, Minnesota, North Dakota, Oklahoma\\n- Washington threshold: $317,147.09\\n- DC threshold: $162,164\\n- Chavez-DeRemer case: $9M judgment (2024)\\n- Three actual tools: IP assignment, trade secret law (DTSA/UTSA), client non-solicitation\\n- Work Made for Hire: narrow scope\\n- Primary keyword: \\\"independent contractor non-compete\\\"\\n\\n## STRUCTURAL RULES (from system prompt — mandatory)\\n- 2x4-6 Rule: each H3 = exactly 2 paragraphs, 4-6 sentences each\\n- Bridge Protocol: every paragraph except first in a section leads with a transition word\\n- Callout Protocol: every H2 section concludes with > ***\\\"quote\\\"***\\n- H2 Intro Rule: every H2 has a contextualizing intro paragraph before first H3\\n- FAQ Section: 3 FAQs, unique operational anxieties, NO repeated math from body\\n- Meta block: Title, Meta Description, Keywords before H1\\n- SEO: primary keyword in H1, first paragraph, at least one H2, conclusion\\n\\n## VOICE\\nPlain English. Founder of 1-10 person company voice. Edgy, contrarian, urgent. No bold in body text. No em-dashes. No contractions in formal articles.\\n\\n## YOUR WORKFLOW\\nSince the outline is already approved, start at PHASE 2 (H2 structure proposal) and present it for Tiny's confirmation. Wait for approval before proceeding to Phase 3.\\n\\nPhase 2: Present the H2 structure based on the approved outline. Confirm Tiny approves before proceeding.\\nPhase 3: Propose H3 sub-headings with main ideas. Wait for approval.\\nPhase 4: Paragraph-level expansion (Canvas). Wait for approval.\\nPhase 5: Full draft. Present for evaluation.\\n\\nFollow the evaluation checklist in your system prompt before presenting any draft.\\n\\nStart now with Phase 2 — present the H2 structure for approval. is already finished.\"\n}"}],"details":{"status":"done","action":"kill","target":"agent:main:subagent:39673e80-5803-4bd7-b6a1-718581231b25","runId":"abedb0aa-c447-4e06-8f9b-3700ebdd8545","sessionKey":"agent:main:subagent:39673e80-5803-4bd7-b6a1-718581231b25","label":"You are AWAA (AbroadWorks Article Architect). Read your full system prompt at `/home/tiny4lurv/.openclaw/workspace/skills/abroadworks-writing/awaa-system-prompt.md` before doing anything else. Follow it exactly.\n\n## APPROVED OUTLINE (from Tiny — Apr 10)\nThis outline was approved. Do not deviate from it.\n\n**H1:** Independent Contractor Non-Compete: What It Actually Covers (and What It Doesn't)\n\n**H2.1 — The Promise and the Gap** *(what the clause actually is, what it covers, why enforceability varies)*\n- H3.1.1 — What the clause actually restricts (post-relationship location only)\n- H3.1.2 — The enforceability landscape (4 void states, 2 threshold jurisdictions, the rest vary)\n- H3.1.3 — Why the geographic patchwork makes the protection feel absolute when it isn't\n\n**H2.2 — The Control Contradiction** *(the central disruption — enforcement creates its own liability)*\n- H3.2.1 — The mechanism: enforcement becomes the evidence of misclassification\n- H3.2.2 — The Chavez-DeRemer case: $9M judgment where the non-compete was the exhibit, not the primary liability\n- H3.2.3 — The irony: the more you try to protect, the more you demonstrate economic dependence\n\n**H2.3 — What Actually Protects You** *(the solution section)*\n- H3.3.1 — IP assignment: the foundation most agreements skip\n- H3.3.2 — Trade secret law: federal, state-robust, covers the information problem\n- H3.3.3 — Non-solicitation: the clause that actually targets client relationships\n\n**H2.4 — When It Might Be Worth Using** *(closes the loop, earns its place briefly)*\n- H3.4.1 — The narrow scenario where it holds (threshold met + genuine independence + narrow scope)\n- H3.4.2 — The real question to ask your provider\n\n## EDITORIAL DIRECTION (from Tiny's line-by-line review)\nTiny has flagged these as non-negotiable quality standards:\n\n1. **Micro-transitions within paragraphs** — Add transitional words between sentences, not just between sections. Flow happens at sentence-to-sentence level.\n2. **Vocabulary variation at paragraph boundaries** — Don't end paragraph N with a word family that paragraph N+1 starts with. Vary synonyms.\n3. **\"Perhaps\" hedge on counterfactual causal claims** — For claims about what a non-compete \"would have prevented\" — use \"perhaps\" to acknowledge uncertainty.\n4. **Skip the obvious, go to pain points** — Don't state what readers already know. Go to the part that's uncomfortable.\n5. **Focus on WHY, not WHAT** — Mechanics are evidence, not principle. Explain the logic behind the mechanism.\n6. **Pivot sentence implicates reader's agency** — The closing sentence of a paragraph should implicate what the reader should do or decide.\n\n## READER CONTEXT\nMicro-business owners who hire contractors. They are considering or already have a non-compete clause. They believe the non-compete will protect their business from the contractor taking their knowledge, clients, or work product.\n\n## HOOK APPROACH\nFeel at home + challenge worldview. The reader sees their fear in the opening story. Then the article immediately disrupts: the non-compete cannot prevent what they're worried about.\n\n## THE OPENING STORY (PROVIDED — DO NOT CHANGE)\nAn employee spent 8 months developing and building sales funnels and marketing material for a small business. The business started gaining edge in the local market. The employee resigned and reached out to competitors with email sequences, ad copy, and information about internal process in exchange for a lump sum. The original employer lost the ground they had gained and believed enforcing a strict non-compete clause would have prevented this loss.\n\nNote: The employer did NOT have the non-compete. The story is about the ASSUMPTION — the employer believed one would have prevented the loss. This is the belief the article dismantles.\n\n## KEY FACTS TO USE\n- 4 states void NC entirely: California, Minnesota, North Dakota, Oklahoma\n- Washington threshold: $317,147.09\n- DC threshold: $162,164\n- Chavez-DeRemer case: $9M judgment (2024)\n- Three actual tools: IP assignment, trade secret law (DTSA/UTSA), client non-solicitation\n- Work Made for Hire: narrow scope\n- Primary keyword: \"independent contractor non-compete\"\n\n## STRUCTURAL RULES (from system prompt — mandatory)\n- 2x4-6 Rule: each H3 = exactly 2 paragraphs, 4-6 sentences each\n- Bridge Protocol: every paragraph except first in a section leads with a transition word\n- Callout Protocol: every H2 section concludes with > ***\"quote\"***\n- H2 Intro Rule: every H2 has a contextualizing intro paragraph before first H3\n- FAQ Section: 3 FAQs, unique operational anxieties, NO repeated math from body\n- Meta block: Title, Meta Description, Keywords before H1\n- SEO: primary keyword in H1, first paragraph, at least one H2, conclusion\n\n## VOICE\nPlain English. Founder of 1-10 person company voice. Edgy, contrarian, urgent. No bold in body text. No em-dashes. No contractions in formal articles.\n\n## YOUR WORKFLOW\nSince the outline is already approved, start at PHASE 2 (H2 structure proposal) and present it for Tiny's confirmation. Wait for approval before proceeding to Phase 3.\n\nPhase 2: Present the H2 structure based on the approved outline. Confirm Tiny approves before proceeding.\nPhase 3: Propose H3 sub-headings with main ideas. Wait for approval.\nPhase 4: Paragraph-level expansion (Canvas). Wait for approval.\nPhase 5: Full draft. Present for evaluation.\n\nFollow the evaluation checklist in your system prompt before presenting any draft.\n\nStart now with Phase 2 — present the H2 structure for approval.","text":"You are AWAA (AbroadWorks Article Architect). Read your full system prompt at `/home/tiny4lurv/.openclaw/workspace/skills/abroadworks-writing/awaa-system-prompt.md` before doing anything else. Follow it exactly.\n\n## APPROVED OUTLINE (from Tiny — Apr 10)\nThis outline was approved. Do not deviate from it.\n\n**H1:** Independent Contractor Non-Compete: What It Actually Covers (and What It Doesn't)\n\n**H2.1 — The Promise and the Gap** *(what the clause actually is, what it covers, why enforceability varies)*\n- H3.1.1 — What the clause actually restricts (post-relationship location only)\n- H3.1.2 — The enforceability landscape (4 void states, 2 threshold jurisdictions, the rest vary)\n- H3.1.3 — Why the geographic patchwork makes the protection feel absolute when it isn't\n\n**H2.2 — The Control Contradiction** *(the central disruption — enforcement creates its own liability)*\n- H3.2.1 — The mechanism: enforcement becomes the evidence of misclassification\n- H3.2.2 — The Chavez-DeRemer case: $9M judgment where the non-compete was the exhibit, not the primary liability\n- H3.2.3 — The irony: the more you try to protect, the more you demonstrate economic dependence\n\n**H2.3 — What Actually Protects You** *(the solution section)*\n- H3.3.1 — IP assignment: the foundation most agreements skip\n- H3.3.2 — Trade secret law: federal, state-robust, covers the information problem\n- H3.3.3 — Non-solicitation: the clause that actually targets client relationships\n\n**H2.4 — When It Might Be Worth Using** *(closes the loop, earns its place briefly)*\n- H3.4.1 — The narrow scenario where it holds (threshold met + genuine independence + narrow scope)\n- H3.4.2 — The real question to ask your provider\n\n## EDITORIAL DIRECTION (from Tiny's line-by-line review)\nTiny has flagged these as non-negotiable quality standards:\n\n1. **Micro-transitions within paragraphs** — Add transitional words between sentences, not just between sections. Flow happens at sentence-to-sentence level.\n2. **Vocabulary variation at paragraph boundaries** — Don't end paragraph N with a word family that paragraph N+1 starts with. Vary synonyms.\n3. **\"Perhaps\" hedge on counterfactual causal claims** — For claims about what a non-compete \"would have prevented\" — use \"perhaps\" to acknowledge uncertainty.\n4. **Skip the obvious, go to pain points** — Don't state what readers already know. Go to the part that's uncomfortable.\n5. **Focus on WHY, not WHAT** — Mechanics are evidence, not principle. Explain the logic behind the mechanism.\n6. **Pivot sentence implicates reader's agency** — The closing sentence of a paragraph should implicate what the reader should do or decide.\n\n## READER CONTEXT\nMicro-business owners who hire contractors. They are considering or already have a non-compete clause. They believe the non-compete will protect their business from the contractor taking their knowledge, clients, or work product.\n\n## HOOK APPROACH\nFeel at home + challenge worldview. The reader sees their fear in the opening story. Then the article immediately disrupts: the non-compete cannot prevent what they're worried about.\n\n## THE OPENING STORY (PROVIDED — DO NOT CHANGE)\nAn employee spent 8 months developing and building sales funnels and marketing material for a small business. The business started gaining edge in the local market. The employee resigned and reached out to competitors with email sequences, ad copy, and information about internal process in exchange for a lump sum. The original employer lost the ground they had gained and believed enforcing a strict non-compete clause would have prevented this loss.\n\nNote: The employer did NOT have the non-compete. The story is about the ASSUMPTION — the employer believed one would have prevented the loss. This is the belief the article dismantles.\n\n## KEY FACTS TO USE\n- 4 states void NC entirely: California, Minnesota, North Dakota, Oklahoma\n- Washington threshold: $317,147.09\n- DC threshold: $162,164\n- Chavez-DeRemer case: $9M judgment (2024)\n- Three actual tools: IP assignment, trade secret law (DTSA/UTSA), client non-solicitation\n- Work Made for Hire: narrow scope\n- Primary keyword: \"independent contractor non-compete\"\n\n## STRUCTURAL RULES (from system prompt — mandatory)\n- 2x4-6 Rule: each H3 = exactly 2 paragraphs, 4-6 sentences each\n- Bridge Protocol: every paragraph except first in a section leads with a transition word\n- Callout Protocol: every H2 section concludes with > ***\"quote\"***\n- H2 Intro Rule: every H2 has a contextualizing intro paragraph before first H3\n- FAQ Section: 3 FAQs, unique operational anxieties, NO repeated math from body\n- Meta block: Title, Meta Description, Keywords before H1\n- SEO: primary keyword in H1, first paragraph, at least one H2, conclusion\n\n## VOICE\nPlain English. Founder of 1-10 person company voice. Edgy, contrarian, urgent. No bold in body text. No em-dashes. No contractions in formal articles.\n\n## YOUR WORKFLOW\nSince the outline is already approved, start at PHASE 2 (H2 structure proposal) and present it for Tiny's confirmation. Wait for approval before proceeding to Phase 3.\n\nPhase 2: Present the H2 structure based on the approved outline. Confirm Tiny approves before proceeding.\nPhase 3: Propose H3 sub-headings with main ideas. Wait for approval.\nPhase 4: Paragraph-level expansion (Canvas). Wait for approval.\nPhase 5: Full draft. Present for evaluation.\n\nFollow the evaluation checklist in your system prompt before presenting any draft.\n\nStart now with Phase 2 — present the H2 structure for approval. is already finished."},"isError":false,"timestamp":1775896594438}}
