{"type":"message","id":"e808b4fa","parentId":"708b86a1","timestamp":"2026-04-11T10:57:23.384Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"\n\nGot it. I can see the differences clearly now.\n\n**H3.1.1 — What the Clause Actually Restricts — First paragraph:**\n\nYou made two changes:\n1. Removed `\"It restricts where they can physically work.\"` — correct. The very next sentence opens with \"Geographic restrictions on employment...\" which says the same thing, just with more substance. Two sentences back-to-back saying the same thing, and the first one is the thinner version. Cut was right.\n2. Removed the closing rhetorical `\"What do you actually need to protect?\"` — the paragraph lands better as a statement than a question. The subsequent paragraph handles the implied transition naturally.\n\n**The fix pattern:** When a sentence merely restates a more specific version that immediately follows it, cut the weaker one. The reader doesn't need the compressed summary before the detailed version. They need the detailed version.\n\nOne observation on what you added: the sentence `\"It can limit what they do with these, however. For example, discussing confidential and non-public information may be a violation.\"` — this fills what was a sharp logical gap in the original. The original went straight from \"does not restrict what they know\" to geographic restrictions with nothing in between. Your addition bridges that gap — it explains *how* the clause actually does restrict something (use of information), which makes the geographic failure more concrete.\n\n**Editorial principle:** When you cut a redundancy, the gap left behind sometimes reveals missing logic. The fix isn't just subtraction — sometimes adding a bridge sentence is what makes the cut right.\n\nNext change?"}],"stopReason":"stop","api":"ollama","provider":"ollama","model":"minimax-m2.7:cloud","usage":{"input":141597,"output":942,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":142539,"cost":{