tractor_non_compete.md\n/home/tiny4lurv/.openclaw/workspace/rag_abroadworks/drafts/independent_contractor_non_compete_v7.md\n/home/tiny4lurv/.openclaw/workspace/rag_abroadworks/drafts/independent_contractor_non_compete_v3.md\n/home/tiny4lurv/.openclaw/workspace/rag_abroadworks/drafts/independent_contractor_non_compete_v6.md\n/home/tiny4lurv/.openclaw/workspace/rag_abroadworks/clean_md/independent_contractor_non_compete.md\n/home/tiny4lurv/.openclaw/workspace/abroadworks/article-independent-contractor-non-compete.md\n/home/tiny4lurv/.openclaw/workspace/abroadworks/article-how-to-fire-an-independent-contractor.md\n/home/tiny4lurv/.openclaw/workspace/abroadworks/article-independent-contractor-non-compete_ORIGINAL.md","cwd":"/home/tiny4lurv/.openclaw/workspace"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1775905584223}}
{"type":"message","id":"e8255a7d","parentId":"07a45f2e","timestamp":"2026-04-11T11:06:29.182Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"toolCall","id":"ollama_call_e6949d0e-f43c-43c6-b1ec-a3ecc29f7699","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"grep -n -i \"confidential\\|non-public\\|proprietary\\|trade secret\\|NDA\\|confidentiality\" /home/tiny4lurv/.openclaw/workspace/rag_abroadworks/clean_md/independent_contractor_non_compete.md | head -30"}}],"stopReason":"toolUse","api":"ollama","provider":"ollama","model":"minimax-m2.7:cloud","usage":{"input":32196,"output":102,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":32298,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"timestamp":1775905589182}}
{"type":"message","id":"fbee8806","parentId":"e8255a7d","timestamp":"2026-04-11T11:06:29.215Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"ollama_call_e6949d0e-f43c-43c6-b1ec-a3ecc29f7699","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"9:Most micro-business owners want a non-compete for the same reason: they are trying to protect one of three things. The client relationships they spent years building. The proprietary knowledge embedded in their processes and systems. The competitive moat they constructed through deliberate work. A non-compete does none of these. It restricts where a contractor can work after the relationship ends — a geographic or market-based exclusion that activates only when the engagement is already over. The basic restriction is narrower than most owners assume, and that narrowness is the gap between what the clause promises and what it delivers.\n11:Consequently, most standard non-competes cover post-relationship conduct only. During the engagement, the contractor is generally free to work elsewhere unless the agreement explicitly says otherwise. Concurrent-work restrictions must be written explicitly and must themselves be reasonable in scope or courts will strike them down. Furthermore, most standard agreements do not include this language, which means the harm most owners are trying to prevent is the harm the clause cannot address. The irony is that the protection owners believe they are buying does not touch the risks they actually face.\n41:The three things most owners are actually trying to protect — client relationships, work product, and proprietary information — require three different tools. None of them is a non-compete. Two are contractual provisions you write into the agreement. One is a statutory framework you invoke by taking specific steps. These are fundamentally different mechanisms, and understanding the distinction is what separates genuine protection from template language that feels safe while leaving the real gaps open.\n43:### IP Assignment: The Contractual Foundation\n45:Intellectual property assignment is the foundation, and it is the provision most template agreements skip. An IP assignment clause transfers ownership of the work product to you as it is created. The Work Made for Hire doctrine under copyright law covers a narrow set of contributions — most software, design, content, and technical deliverables fall outside it. Without an explicit assignment clause, the contractor retains copyright to what they built for you. You paid for it. You do not own it. Any agreement that does not include an explicit IP assignment clause leaves the work product in the contractor's legal possession even after you have paid in full.\n47:### Trade Secret Law: The Statutory Backstop\n49:Trade secret law provides complementary protection, and it operates differently. The Defend Trade Secrets Act and the Uniform Trade Secrets Act protect proprietary information subject to reasonable confidentiality measures. You do not draft trade secret law into existence — you invoke it by marking your information as proprietary and including a confidentiality clause in the agreement. Once invoked, you have federal and state-level recourse if a contractor misappropriates what belongs to you. Crucially, this does not restrict where the contractor works. It restricts what they do with what they took. Unlike a non-compete, which varies in enforceability by state and income, trade secret protection exists at the federal level and does not depend on where your contractor is based.\n53:Non-solicitation addresses the third risk — client relationships. This is a contractual provision you write into the agreement. It restricts the contractor from taking your clients or employees after the relationship ends. Unlike a non-compete, which restricts where someone may work, a non-solicitation clause targets the specific harm: the relationships you built, the clients you serve, the people who followed your contractor out the door. The three tools work together. IP assignment covers the work product. Trade secret law covers the information. Non-solicitation covers the clients. None restricts where a contractor may work. All restrict what a contractor may do with what belongs to you.\n55:> ***\"The protection you actually need — your work product, your information, your client relationships — comes from IP assignment, trade secret law, and non-solicitation clauses. None of these require a non-compete to function.\"***\n61:For most micro-business owners, the underlying worry is an information problem or a client problem — not a geographic market problem. Non-competes do not address either. The tools that do — IP assignment, confidentiality clauses, client non-solicitation — are enforceable regardless of where the contractor works or where your business is based. The question to ask is not \"do we have a non-compete?\" The question is \"do we have IP assignment, confidentiality, and client non-solicitation?\" If the answer to the second set is yes, the non-compete is optional. If the answer is no, the non-compete is irrelevant.\n75:Only if your agreement explicitly includes a concurrent-work restriction. Most standard non-competes cover post-relationship conduct only and say nothing about what happens while the engagement is active. A concurrent-work restriction must be written explicitly, must define the scope of the restriction, and must itself be reasonable in scope or courts will strike it down. Even with a concurrent-work restriction in place, you must ensure the relationship looks genuinely independent — otherwise the restriction itself becomes evidence of control that a court may use against you."}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":0,"durationMs":12,"aggregated":"9:Most micro-business owners want a non-compete for the same reason: they are trying to protect one of three things. The client relationships they spent years building. The proprietary knowledge embedded in their processes and systems. The competitive moat they constructed through deliberate work. A non-compete does none of these. It restricts where a contractor can work after the relationship ends — a geographic or market-based exclusion that activates only when the engagement is already over. The basic restriction is narrower than most owners assume, and that narrowness is the gap between what the clause promises and what it delivers.\n11:Consequently, most standard non-competes cover post-relationship conduct only. During the engagement, the contractor is generally free to work elsewhere unless the agreement explicitly says otherwise. Concurrent-work restrictions must be written explicitly and must themselves be reasonable in scope or courts will strike them down. Furthermore, most standard agreements do not include this language, which means the harm most owners are trying to prevent is the harm the clause cannot address. The irony is that the protection owners believe they are buying does not touch the risks they actually face.\n41:The three things most owners are actually trying to protect — client relationships, work product, and proprietary information — require three different tools. None of them is a non-compete. Two are contractual provisions you write into the agreement. One is a statutory framework you invoke by taking specific steps. These are fundamentally different mechanisms, and understanding the distinction is what separates genuine protection from template language that feels safe while leaving the real gaps open.\n43:### IP Assignment: The Contractual Foundation\n45:Intellectual property assignment is the foundation, and it is the provision most template agreements skip. An IP assignment clause transfers ownership of the work product to you as it is created. The Work Made for Hire doctrine under copyright law covers a narrow set of contributions — most software, design, content, and technical deliverables fall outside it. Without an explicit assignment clause, the contractor retains copyright to what they built for you. You paid for it. You do not own it. Any agreement that does not include an explicit IP assignment clause leaves the work product in the contractor's legal possession even after you have paid in full.\n47:### Trade Secret Law: The Statutory Backstop\n49:Trade secret law provides complementary protection, and it operates differently. The Defend Trade Secrets Act and the Uniform Trade Secrets Act protect proprietary information subject to reasonable confidentiality measures. You do not draft trade secret law into existence — you invoke it by marking your information as proprietary and including a confidentiality clause in the agreement. Once invoked, you have federal and state-level recourse if a contractor misappropriates what belongs to you. Crucially, this does not restrict where the contractor works. It restricts what they do with what they took. Unlike a non-compete, which varies in enforceability by state and income, trade secret protection exists at the federal level and does not depend on where your contractor is based.\n53:Non-solicitation addresses the third risk — client relationships. This is a contractual provision you write into the agreement. It restricts the contractor from taking your clients or employees after the relationship ends. Unlike a non-compete, which restricts where someone may work, a non-solicitation clause targets the specific harm: the relationships you built, the clients you serve, the people who followed your contractor out the door. The three tools work together. IP assignment covers the work product. Trade secret law covers the information. Non-solicitation covers the clients. None restricts where a contractor may work. All restrict what a contractor may do with what belongs to you.\n55:> ***\"The protection you actually need — your work product, your information, your client relationships — comes from IP assignment, trade secret law, and non-solicitation clauses. None of these require a non-compete to function.\"***\n61:For most micro-business owners, the underlying worry is an information problem or a client problem — not a geographic market problem. Non-competes do not address either. The tools that do — IP assignment, confidentiality clauses, client non-solicitation — are enforceable regardless of where the contractor works or where your business is based. The question to ask is not \"do we have a non-compete?\" The question is \"do we have IP assignment, confidentiality, and client non-solicitation?\" If the answer to the second set is yes, the non-compete is optional. If the answer is no, the non-compete is irrelevant.\n75:Only if your agreement explicitly includes a concurrent-work restriction. Most standard non-competes cover post-relationship conduct only and say nothing about what happens while the engagement is active. A concurrent-work restriction must be written explicitly, must define the scope of the restriction, and must itself be reasonable in scope or courts will strike it down. Even with a concurrent-work restriction in place, you must ensure the relationship looks genuinely independent — otherwise the restriction itself becomes evidence of control that a court may use against you.","cwd":"/home/tiny4lurv/.openclaw/workspace"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1775905589204}}
{"type":"message","id":"62b41328","parentId":"fbee8806","timestamp":"2026-04-11T11:06:48.719Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"It does. Line 9 of the research lists \"proprietary knowledge embedded in their processes and systems\" as one of the three things owners try to protect. Lines 47-49 cover trade secret law and confidentiality clauses specifically — \"invoking\" trade secret protection by marking information as proprietary and including a confidentiality clause in the agreement.\n\nSo the confidentiality material is in the research. I misidentified it as AWAA drift when you added it — but you were right to add it because it's explicitly in the source. My mistake.\n\nThe distinction is real though: the research talks about confidentiality as something you invoke contractually, which is different from what the non-compete clause actually restricts. That's probably why it felt like a tangent — it's covered in the research but the non-compete itself doesn't touch it."}],"stopReason":"stop","api":"ollama","provider":"ollama","model":"minimax-m2.7:cloud","usage":{"input":33301,"output":365,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":33666,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"timestamp":1775905608716}}
