{"type":"message","id":"205f1438","parentId":"72caae03","timestamp":"2026-04-11T11:24:43.001Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"toolCall","id":"ollama_call_a36605e8-8714-4f73-8bd4-179eb7e57325","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"iconv -f UTF-16LE -t UTF-8 /home/tiny4lurv/.openclaw/workspace/awaa-output/phase-5-pre-tiny-review.md 2>/dev/null | sed -n '/### The Enforceability Landscape/,/### Why the Geographic Patchwork/p' | head -60"}}],"stopReason":"toolUse","api":"ollama","provider":"ollama","model":"minimax-m2.7:cloud","usage":{"input":62580,"output":120,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":62700,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"timestamp":1775906683001}}
{"type":"message","id":"83b1082c","parentId":"205f1438","timestamp":"2026-04-11T11:24:43.029Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"ollama_call_a36605e8-8714-4f73-8bd4-179eb7e57325","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"### The Enforceability Landscape\r\n\r\nThe clause is not just limited. It is outright void in four states, and those states are not exotic outliers. California, Minnesota, North Dakota, and Oklahoma prohibit non-competes for independent contractors entirely. These are not small or irrelevant markets. California alone represents the fifth-largest economy in the world, and the state's technology and freelance sectors mean a significant portion of your remote contractor workforce may be working from jurisdictions where the clause you relied on is void on its face. The assumption that the clause protects your contractor relationships because most states allow it is the first layer of the gap.\r\n\r\nEven in states where the clause is technically enforceable, dollar thresholds apply. Washington requires annual compensation or contract value above $317,147.09 before a non-compete can be enforced against a contractor. DC sets the bar at $162,164. These thresholds are not minor bureaucratic obstacles. They are structural gates that eliminate most small and micro-business contractor relationships from protection entirely. A contractor billing $25,000 for a three-month engagement falls below both thresholds in virtually every configuration. If your contractor arrangements do not clear the threshold, the clause you drafted and relied on is not a protection. It is decoration.\r\n\r\n### Why the Geographic Patchwork Makes the Protection Feel Absolute When It Is Not"}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":0,"durationMs":10,"aggregated":"### The Enforceability Landscape\r\n\r\nThe clause is not just limited. It is outright void in four states, and those states are not exotic outliers. California, Minnesota, North Dakota, and Oklahoma prohibit non-competes for independent contractors entirely. These are not small or irrelevant markets. California alone represents the fifth-largest economy in the world, and the state's technology and freelance sectors mean a significant portion of your remote contractor workforce may be working from jurisdictions where the clause you relied on is void on its face. The assumption that the clause protects your contractor relationships because most states allow it is the first layer of the gap.\r\n\r\nEven in states where the clause is technically enforceable, dollar thresholds apply. Washington requires annual compensation or contract value above $317,147.09 before a non-compete can be enforced against a contractor. DC sets the bar at $162,164. These thresholds are not minor bureaucratic obstacles. They are structural gates that eliminate most small and micro-business contractor relationships from protection entirely. A contractor billing $25,000 for a three-month engagement falls below both thresholds in virtually every configuration. If your contractor arrangements do not clear the threshold, the clause you drafted and relied on is not a protection. It is decoration.\r\n\r\n### Why the Geographic Patchwork Makes the Protection Feel Absolute When It Is Not","cwd":"/home/tiny4lurv/.openclaw/workspace"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1775906683020}}
{"type":"message","id":"94eff4f0","parentId":"83b1082c","timestamp":"2026-04-11T11:25:01.072Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"\nHere's what changed in H3.1.2 (The Enforceability Landscape):\n\n**Opening sentence — before and after:**\n\n*Before (reference):*\n> \"The clause is not just limited. It is outright void in four states, and those states are not exotic outliers.\"\n\n*After (your edit):*\n> \"Just as the clause's impact on a contractor is limited, the legal framework itself is geographically limited. It is outright void in four states, and those states are not exotic outliers.\"\n\n**The change:** You caught and removed the \"X is not just Y\" strawman pattern (\"The clause is not just limited\") — the same prohibited structure we identified in the Non-Solicitation section. The replacement is a proper transitional bridge: it nods to the previous section's point (the clause's limited impact) while cleanly pivoting to the new material (geographic unenforceability).\n\nEverything else in H3.1.2 appears unchanged from the reference copy.\n\nIs that accurate?"}],"stopReason":"stop","api":"ollama","provider":"ollama","model":"minimax-m2.7:cloud","usage":{"input":62943,"output":625,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":63568,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"timestamp":1775906701070}}
