{"type":"message","id":"31c1814c","parentId":"43b561ec","timestamp":"2026-04-11T11:59:44.769Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"ollama_call_b52303de-e628-4825-a301-ea5ecd0f8d85","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"## The Control Contradiction\r\n\r\nThere is a second problem with non-competes that most articles do not mention, and it runs in the opposite direction from the first. The clause does not just fail to protect you. Used aggressively, it can actively create liability. The mechanism is counterintuitive and it works like this. Courts determine whether a worker is an independent contractor or an employee by examining the degree of control the hiring business exercises over that worker. The more control you exert, the more the relationship looks like employment. Non-competes are a control mechanism, which means using one is itself evidence of the relationship you are trying to deny. This is the control contradiction, and it is the most consequential flaw in the standard approach to protecting contractor relationships.\r\n\r\n### The Mechanism: Enforcement Becomes the Evidence of Misclassification"}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":0,"durationMs":12,"aggregated":"## The Control Contradiction\r\n\r\nThere is a second problem with non-competes that most articles do not mention, and it runs in the opposite direction from the first. The clause does not just fail to protect you. Used aggressively, it can actively create liability. The mechanism is counterintuitive and it works like this. Courts determine whether a worker is an independent contractor or an employee by examining the degree of control the hiring business exercises over that worker. The more control you exert, the more the relationship looks like employment. Non-competes are a control mechanism, which means using one is itself evidence of the relationship you are trying to deny. This is the control contradiction, and it is the most consequential flaw in the standard approach to protecting contractor relationships.\r\n\r\n### The Mechanism: Enforcement Becomes the Evidence of Misclassification","cwd":"/home/tiny4lurv/.openclaw/workspace"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1775908784756}}
{"type":"message","id":"cefb8e34","parentId":"31c1814c","timestamp":"2026-04-11T12:00:04.974Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"The intro and H3.3.1 are both doing the same job.\n\nThe intro says: \"The mechanism is counterintuitive and it works like this. Courts determine whether a worker is an independent contractor or an employee by examining the degree of control.\"\n\nThen H3.3.1 opens with: \"Courts determine whether a worker is an employee or an independent contractor by looking at the degree of control the hiring business exercises.\"\n\nThe intro promises to explain the mechanism. H3.3.1 then explains the mechanism — again, almost word-for-word. The intro isn't previewing what's coming. It's starting the argument one paragraph early, then H3.3.1 repeats it.\n\nThe intro should do one job: tell the reader *what* the second problem is and why it matters, without explaining *how* it works. H3.3.1 then owns the how.\n\n\"The mechanism is counterintuitive and it works like this\" is also a classic AI template — it's filler that signals \"I'm about to explain\" without actually framing the explanation.\n\nYour edit removed the meta-structure (\"runs in the opposite direction from the first\") and the template filler, which fixes the parrotting problem. But the deeper structural issue is: **the intro was one paragraph that tried to be two things — a framing paragraph and a first-H3 paragraph — and both suffered.**"}],"stopReason":"stop","api":"ollama","provider":"ollama","model":"minimax-m2.7:cloud","usage":{"input":67569,"output":640,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":68209,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"timestamp":1775908804972}}
