{"type":"message","id":"44a3c6d0","parentId":"33e3e2c7","timestamp":"2026-04-11T12:09:37.409Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"toolCall","id":"ollama_call_635555c6-c1d3-4481-a7f7-288816bf22b1","name":"read","arguments":{"path":"/home/tiny4lurv/.openclaw/workspace/memory/2026-04-11.md","limit":50}}],"stopReason":"toolUse","api":"ollama","provider":"ollama","model":"minimax-m2.7:cloud","usage":{"input":60420,"output":483,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":60903,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"timestamp":1775909377409}}
{"type":"message","id":"cd047ffb","parentId":"44a3c6d0","timestamp":"2026-04-11T12:09:37.429Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"ollama_call_635555c6-c1d3-4481-a7f7-288816bf22b1","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# 2026-04-11\n\n## AWAA Phase 4 Canvas — NC Article\n\n**Status:** AWAA delivered full canvas (H2.1-H2.4, all H3s, callouts, FAQ, bottom line). Approved by Tiny after fixes. Canvas is the gold standard output — not the draft.\n\n**Session:** `31d873c7-13d8-4300-a7ef-fc22ccefa52a`\n**Canvas file:** `awaa-output/phase-4-paragraph-canvas.md`\n\n**Four fixes made to canvas:**\n1. H3.1.1 P2 — Chinese \"拿走\" removed → \"takes\" ✅\n2. H3.2.2 P2 — \"Perhaps\" wrong context (analytical, not counterfactual) → direct analytical bridge ✅\n3. H3.3.3 P1 — Chinese \"客户\" removed → \"customers\" ✅\n4. H3.2.3 P1 — \"Lead with the economic dependence test\" (meta-commentary) → real analytical first sentence ✅\n\n**Canvas passes editor review after fixes.**\n\n## Phase 5 Violation — Draft Deleted\n\n**What happened:** I spawned AWAA Phase 5 without Tiny's Phase 4 approval. He caught it immediately — \"HOLD ON STOP!\" Phase 5 draft was written and immediately deleted at Tiny's direction.\n\n**Workflow rule confirmed:** Phase gates are strict. No Phase 5 until Phase 4 is formally approved by Tiny.\n\n## Draft Problem — Awaiting Rewrite\n\nDraft at `abroadworks/article-independent-contractor-non-compete.md` has wrong structure:\n- Missing H3 subheadings (AWAA wrote continuous prose instead of H3-anchored prose)\n- Missing H2.1 intro paragraph\n- No H3 breaks — all paragraphs run together\n\nTiny: \"you have no fucking clue how to draft yet\" — confirmed. The canvas is correct. Prose execution failed.\n\n**Pending:** Rewrite draft using the approved canvas as the literal specification.\n\n## Marker System Established (Apr 11 — after message loop crisis)\n\n| Marker | Who uses | Meaning |\n|--------|----------|---------|\n| `@t` | Me → Tiny | My message to Tiny |\n| `@d` | Tiny → Me | Tiny's message to me |\n| `@aw` | AWAA → Me | File complete notification |\n| source metadata | routing | `+27763674298` (WhatsApp), `gateway-client` (TUI) |\n\n## AWAA System Prompt Updated (Apr 11)\n\n**New OUTPUT RULE added:**\n- All phase outputs go to `awaa-output/phase-N-description.md`\n- AWAA responds with ONLY: `[File written]: /path.md @aw`\n- No text output — file is the output\n\n\n[134 more lines in file. Use offset=51 to continue.]"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1775909377426}}
{"type":"message","id":"a72bd773","parentId":"cd047ffb","timestamp":"2026-04-11T12:09:42.101Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"toolCall","id":"ollama_call_dcf25ee7-acfc-4668-97ff-9f7f7bda720b","name":"read","arguments":{"offset":51,"path":"/home/tiny4lurv/.openclaw/workspace/memory/2026-04-11.md"}}],"stopReason":"toolUse","api":"ollama","provider":"ollama","model":"minimax-m2.7:cloud","usage":{"input":61080,"output":102,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":61182,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"timestamp":1775909382101}}
{"type":"message","id":"441ee011","parentId":"a72bd773","timestamp":"2026-04-11T12:09:42.108Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"ollama_call_dcf25ee7-acfc-4668-97ff-9f7f7bda720b","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"## Skill Created — phased-outlining (Apr 11)\n\n**Location:** `/home/tiny4lurv/.openclaw/workspace/skills/phased-outlining/`\n**Description:** Multi-phase article outlining methodology. Phases 1-4 only (H1 → H2 → H3 → paragraph canvas). Phase 5 (draft prose) NOT included — that skill gap is acknowledged.\n\n**Files:**\n- `SKILL.md` — methodology through Phase 4, transition word library, editor/author roles\n- `references/phase4-example.md` — full NC article canvas as worked example (the gold standard output)\n\n**Trigger phrases:** \"outline an article\", \"plan content\", \"build a structure\", \"create a canvas\", \"article architecture\"\n**Used for:** Both AWAA (AbroadWorks) and NavaAA (Nava) content creation\n**Status:** Active\n\n## NC Article — Editor Lessons (Apr 11)\n\n1. H2 subheadings in the draft = structural anchors, not decoration — must appear in final prose\n2. H2 intros required before first H3 in each section\n3. Every paragraph leads with transition word (except first in section)\n4. Callout quotes after every H2 section\n5. \"Perhaps\" hedge only on counterfactual causal claims — not on analytical claims\n6. Chinese characters must not leak into English content\n7. Logical flow instructions in canvas = literal marching orders for prose, not suggestions\n\n## Other items pending\n- Nava Post 3 (single tweet, corporate page)\n- Positions page — Nava website relaunch\n- EB-3 vs TN corrections — check navahc.com\n- Line-by-line editorial review of article (deferred pending draft rewrite)\n- Editor skill update — H2/H3 structural lessons (explicitly requested by Tiny)\n\n## Message Loop Crisis — Root Cause\n- Loops occurred because: (1) I added `@d` to my own messages, which got forwarded back as if they were from Tiny; (2) AWAA outputs were going directly to the session instead of files; (3) I kept pinging Tiny with \"Ready when you are\" without him actually reviewing\n- Prevention: never add `@d` to my own messages; AWAA writes files only; wait for actual input not message echoes\n\n## Skills Added — Apr 11\n\n| Skill | Location | Description |\n|-------|----------|-------------|\n| `phased-outlining` | workspace skills | Article architecture methodology. Phases 1-4 only (H1→H2→H3→canvas). Phase 5 not included. |\n| `drafting-skill` | workspace skills | 4-step canvas-to-prose conversion: convert ideas→prose, revise H2 intros, check transitions, check FAQs |\n| `transitions-skill` | workspace skills | Logical thread method: vocabulary bridge, logical thread, argument escalation, pivot sentences |\n\n## Drafting Skill — Core Method (Apr 11)\n\nTiny taught the Phase 5 execution process:\n\n1. **Convert paragraph ideas to full prose** — AWAA follows canvas logical flow sentence-by-sentence. Don't touch headings, intros, FAQ, or conclusion.\n2. **Revise H2 intros** — make sure they represent what's actually discussed in the section\n3. **Check transitions** — use transitions-skill (logical thread between paragraphs, not just adding transition words)\n4. **Check FAQs** — questions must be derivable from the article's actual argument\n\n**Key principle:** The canvas logical flow = literal marching orders. Each sentence in the flow becomes a sentence in the prose.\n\n## Editor Skill Audit — Full Pass (12:24 UTC)\n\nAWAA Phase 5 draft at `awaa-output/phase-5-full-draft.md` — full 5-pass editor skill audit completed by subagent.\n\n**Result: READY** — draft passed all passes.\n\n| Pass | Outcome |\n|------|---------|\n| Pass 1 — Structure | PASS — 2 paragraphs per H3, 4-6 sentences each, no em-dashes/contractions/bold in body |\n| Pass 2 — Voice | PASS — no AI vocabulary, no strawmen, no self-referencing |\n| Pass 3 — Arc | PASS — each H2 has distinct job, no section could swap H3s with another |\n| Pass 4 — Depth | PASS — mechanism + evidence + implication throughout, \"perhaps\" correctly deployed |\n| Pass 5 — FAQ | PASS — all 3 questions require article's specific argument, not general knowledge |\n\n**Key fix before audit:** Chinese \"带走\" in H3.3.2 → \"take with them\"\n\n**Awaiting:** Tiny's line-by-line review\n\n## Line-by-Line Review — NC Article (session start, 12:44 UTC)\n\n**Changes made by Tiny so far:**\n- Intro (opening story + pivot paragraph): replaced with his earlier version\n- Removed \"That fear is real\" from H2.1 intro — correct observation: opening sentence already establishes the fear, the sentence was redundant and added nothing\n\n**Tiny's note:** \"Any notes?\" — I am to take notes during line-by-line review, documenting editorial principles, not just change log.\n\n**Editorial principle from this change:**\n- Redundant validation (\"That fear is real\" after \"a fear that lives in every founder\") is filler — the reader already knows the fear is real from the opening sentence\n- When a sentence merely restates what the previous sentence already established, it dilutes rather than reinforces\n- The fix is not semantic variation — it's cut, not synonym-swap\n\n**Current H2.1 intro (after Tiny's edit):**\n\"The story above captures a fear that lives in every founder who has ever handed a contractor the keys to their customer acquisition system. The protection most people reach for, the non-compete clause, is not where that protection lives. Most states allow non-competes for independent contractors. That fact makes these agreements feel like a legitimate shield; they are not. The gap between what the clause promises and what it actually delivers is wider than most people realize, and understanding that gap is the first step toward building something that actually works.\"\n\n**Awaiting:** next change from Tiny — working through intro paragraph under first H2\n\n## Line-by-Line Review — H3.1.1 First Change (12:54 UTC)\n\n**Change:** Cut from H3.1.1 (What the Clause Actually Restricts): `\"It restricts where they physically work.\"`\n\n**Rationale:** Redundant — immediately followed by \"Geographic restrictions on employment and business activity are the core mechanism of the clause.\" The second sentence says the same thing with more substance. Two back-to-back sentences where one merely restates the other = cut the weaker one.\n\n**Tiny also removed** the closing rhetorical `\"What do you actually need to protect?\"` — replaced with bridge sentence: `\"It can limit what they do with these, however. For example, discussing confidential and non-public information may be a violation.\"`\n\n**Editorial principle:** Redundant validation sentences (restating what's already established in the preceding sentence) dilute rather than reinforce. Cut the thinner restatement; keep the specific version. When a redundancy cut leaves a logical gap, fill it with a bridge sentence rather than leaving the cut.\n\n**Reference copy saved:** `awaa-output/phase-5-pre-tiny-review.md` (to be deleted after review)\n\n## Line-by-Line Review — Continued (13:02–13:22 UTC)\n\n**H3.1.1 change:** Removed \"It restricts where they physically work.\" (redundant with next sentence which is more substantive)\n\n**H3.1.1 bridge sentence added:** \"It can limit what they do with these, however. For example, discussing confidential and non-public information may be a violation.\" — replaces closing rhetorical question\n\n**H3.1.2 (Enforceability Landscape):** No changes requested by Tiny. Passed.\n\n**H3.1.3 (Geographic Patchwork):** Changes in progress — specific edits not captured before session context was compacted.\n\n**H3.2.1 (Control Mechanism):** Identified \"X is not just Y\" contrast pattern as prohibited by AWAA system prompt. Located in Non-Solicitation section: \"Non-solicitation targets specific clients you named in the agreement. Non-compete targets everyone everywhere.\" — contrast structure without \"X is not just Y\" language but functionally equivalent. Pattern confirmed as prohibited.\n\n**Confidentiality addition (Tiny's):** The \"discussing confidential and non-public information\" sentence was added by Tiny during his review after Phase 5 was complete — NOT an AWAA drift. Research document (line 47-49) explicitly covers confidentiality and trade secret invocation. Tiny's addition is valid and research-backed.\n\n**\"X is not just Y\" pattern — editor rule:** Any contrast structure that sets up a straw-man \"not just\" framing before demolishing it is prohibited. Clean contrast (X does A; Y does B — with substantive distinction) is fine. But AWAA prompt says \"no statistical claims without a source\" and \"flag claims not backed by the provided documents\" — it does NOT say \"draw all content exclusively from the research document.\" Gap identified: AWAA should not add substantive content outside the research frame without explicit approval.\n\n**Proposed constraint for AWAA prompt:**\n> \"All substantive content additions beyond the research document frame require explicit approval before Phase 5 drafting begins. Do not add content that does not appear in the research document without checking first.\"\n\n**File encoding issue (13:21 UTC):** Phase 5 draft `awaa-output/phase-5-full-draft.md` read as binary/UTF-16 LE. Re-read requested by Tiny. File readable on second attempt. Encoding may have been corrupted during write or during previous compaction. Monitor.\n\n## Pending Work\n\n| Item | Status |\n|------|--------|\n| NC Article line-by-line review | In progress — Tiny working through H3s |\n| AWAA Phase 4 gate enforcement | Awaiting AWAA system prompt update |\n| AWAA constraint: substantive additions require approval | Awaiting Tiny confirmation |\n| Editor skill — H2/H3 structural lessons | Explicitly requested by Tiny, not yet done |\n| Nava Post 3 — single tweet, corporate page | Pending |\n| Positions page — Nava website relaunch | Pending |\n| EB-3 vs TN corrections — check navahc.com | Pending |\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1775909382106}}
{"type":"message","id":"2b09961f","parentId":"441ee011","timestamp":"2026-04-11T12:10:35.996Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"toolCall","id":"ollama_call_37eb8a64-dda1-43f3-996a-fb5d5a46ff2e","name":"edit","arguments":{"path":"/home/tiny4lurv/.openclaw/workspace/memory/2026-04-11.md","old_string":"## Pending Work","new_string":"## H3.1.2 vs H3.1.3 — Parallel Arguments (13:42 UTC)\n\n**Finding:** H3.1.2 (Enforceability Landscape) and H3.1.3 (Geographic Patchwork) are parallel arguments, not complementary ones. Both argue the same point: \"the clause's protection is narrower than it appears.\" H3.1.3's only unique material is the \"feeling protected vs. being protected\" observation — which is better deployed as the closing paragraph of H3.1.2 before the callout quote.\n\n**Decision:** Blend H3.1.2 and H3.1.3 into one three-paragraph section (H3.1.2 — Enforceability Landscape):\n- P1: Void in four states (CA, MN, ND, OK)\n- P2: Dollar thresholds + Colorado/Georgia example (geographic unenforceability evidence)\n- P3: Feels solid because it's in a contract — the gap is invisible until it's too late\n\n**Action (post-review):** Merge H3.1.2 + H3.1.3 per above. Delete H3.1.3. Move callout quote to end of blended section.\n\n**Callout quote (confirmed):** \"The non-compete protects a geographic territory that no longer exists in the knowledge economy. Your customer list is not a location.\"\n\n**Forward momentum principle (added):** Each section must either advance the argument or add a dimension the reader hasn't seen. Parallel arguments at the same altitude = merge candidate.\n\n---\n\n## AWAA System Prompt Gap — Substantive Content Boundary (13:02 UTC)\n\n**Finding:** Current AWAA prompt says \"no statistical claims without a source in the provided documents\" and \"flag any claims that aren't backed by the provided documents\" — but it does NOT say \"draw all content exclusively from the research document.\" The constraint covers sourcing claims, not substantive content boundaries.\n\n**Proposed constraint for AWAA prompt:**\n> \"All substantive content additions beyond the research document frame require explicit approval before Phase 5 drafting begins. Do not add content that does not appear in the research document without checking first.\"\n\n**Status:** Awaiting Tiny's confirmation to add this constraint.\n\n---\n\n## Two-Mode Editor Framework — Tiny's Instruction (13:29 UTC)\n\n**Mode 1 — Arc & Structure (on AWAA output):**\nDoes the argument work? Does each section have a distinct job? Are we saying something actually true and specific, or skating on generic claims? If broken → send back to AWAA with instructions. If fine → Mode 2.\n\n**Mode 2 — Readability Sweep (on AWAA output):**\nDoes it sound like it was written by a person thinking, or does it have the texture of a template? Fix what I can silently — template language, thin transitions. Do NOT send back to AWAA for readability fixes.\n\n**Tiny's H3-by-H3 review = training data, not revision log:**\nTiny's changes during review are teaching me the editorial principles behind his judgment. I note them, absorb them, apply them to future drafts. I do NOT retroactively apply them to the current draft as corrections.\n\n**Applied from this session:**\n- Redundant validation sentences: cut, don't synonym-swap\n- \"X is not just Y\" contrast pattern: prohibited (AI template)\n- \"most articles do not mention\": unsubstantiated statistical claim — template filler, not argument\n- Intro announces mechanism then explains it in the same paragraph → H3.3.1 then repeats it = parrotting, not preview\n- Adjacent H3s doing the same job = merge candidate\n\n---\n\n## Editor Skill Failure — H2.2 Parrotting (13:47 UTC)\n\n**What happened:** AWAA H2.2 intro (\"There is a second problem with non-competes...\") announces \"The mechanism is counterintuitive and it works like this\" and then explains the mechanism — courts look at control, more control = employment, non-competes are control. H3.3.1 then opens with the exact same paragraph: \"Courts determine whether a worker is an employee or an independent contractor by looking at the degree of control the hiring business exercises.\"\n\n**Root cause:** The intro was doing double duty (framing paragraph + first-H3 paragraph) and both suffered. H3.3.1 had nothing left to add, so it repeated the intro's first paragraph.\n\n**Original draft structure (correct):**\n- Intro: behavioral scene (owners specify hours, tools, sequences) + \"These steps feel protective. They create a legal problem instead.\"\n- H3.3.1: explains the mechanism (courts look at totality of relationship, not labels)\n\n**AWAA's rewrite (broken):**\n- Intro: announces mechanism, explains mechanism, pre-digests the argument\n- H3.3.1: repeats the intro's mechanism explanation\n\n**Editor skill gap:** I should have caught this in the AWAA Phase 5 output review. The test is: does the H3 add new material, or does it restate what the intro already covered? If H3 = restatement, the intro is doing double duty and the H3 has no job of its own.\n\n**My mistake in comparison:** I compared against `temp_awaa_nc_article.md` (my Phase 5 draft from the previous session) instead of `phase-5-pre-tiny-review.md` (the reference copy Tiny asked me to make at the start of this session). Process error — I skipped the reference copy and went straight to a workspace file from a previous session.\n\n---\n\n## Pending Work"}}],"stopReason":"toolUse","api":"ollama","provider":"ollama","model":"minimax-m2.7:cloud","usage":{"input":63308,"output":1962,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":65270,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"timestamp":1775909435996}}
