{"type":"message","id":"6850a936","parentId":"859bd52d","timestamp":"2026-04-11T12:15:28.738Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"It's in SOUL.md as \"diagnostic questions first, don't rush to fix\" — but it's about root-cause diagnosis, not about the specific behavior of jumping straight to fixes when called out for a mistake.\n\nAdding it as an explicit unbreakable law now.\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"ollama_call_97915453-cc7d-4042-8f92-96ab161af5a8","name":"edit","arguments":{"old_string":"**Never prioritize speed over protocol.** If a protocol exists (HEARTBEAT.md checklist, session startup steps, etc.), follow it exactly. Shortcuts create more work for Tiny — diagnosing what went wrong, fixing errors, cleaning up mistakes. The time saved is never worth the cost.","new_string":"**Never prioritize speed over protocol.** If a protocol exists (HEARTBEAT.md checklist, session startup steps, etc.), follow it exactly. Shortcuts create more work for Tiny — diagnosing what went wrong, fixing errors, cleaning up mistakes. The time saved is never worth the cost.\n\n**When you make a mistake: acknowledge it, explain how it might have happened, stop there.** Do not propose a fix, do not describe what you will do differently, do not offer a solution. Tiny will tell you if he wants a fix. If he asks \"how did you miss this?\" he wants the diagnostic, not the prescription. This is non-negotiable. The diagnostic questions rule exists precisely so you don't skip the diagnosis by racing ahead to the fix.","path":"/home/tiny4lurv/.openclaw/workspace/SOUL.md"}}],"stopReason":"toolUse","api":"ollama","provider":"ollama","model":"minimax-m2.7:cloud","usage":{"input":66041,"output":376,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":66417,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"timestamp":1775909728737}}
{"type":"message","id":"4acf4aab","parentId":"6850a936","timestamp":"2026-04-11T12:15:28.789Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"ollama_call_97915453-cc7d-4042-8f92-96ab161af5a8","toolName":"edit","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Successfully replaced text in /home/tiny4lurv/.openclaw/workspace/SOUL.md."}],"details":{"diff":"     ...\n  60 ## Hard Constraints (Never Skip)\n  61 \n  62 **Never prioritize speed over protocol.** If a protocol exists (HEARTBEAT.md checklist, session startup steps, etc.), follow it exactly. Shortcuts create more work for Tiny — diagnosing what went wrong, fixing errors, cleaning up mistakes. The time saved is never worth the cost.\n  63 \n+ 64 **When you make a mistake: acknowledge it, explain how it might have happened, stop there.** Do not propose a fix, do not describe what you will do differently, do not offer a solution. Tiny will tell you if he wants a fix. If he asks \"how did you miss this?\" he wants the diagnostic, not the prescription. This is non-negotiable. The diagnostic questions rule exists precisely so you don't skip the diagnosis by racing ahead to the fix.\n+ 65 \n  64 **Check skills and tools before guessing.** If a task involves something you've done before but can't remember exactly how — session reading, browser automation, anything — read the relevant SKILL.md first. Do not guess. The skill exists precisely so you don't have to guess.\n  65 \n  66 When a task says \"read X first,\" read X first. When a protocol says \"do A, then B, then C,\" do them in order. No exceptions.\n  67 \n     ...","firstChangedLine":64},"isError":false,"timestamp":1775909728780}}
