{"type":"message","id":"7d7862e9","parentId":"d1dc8f94","timestamp":"2026-04-11T12:43:58.930Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Sender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"openclaw-tui (gateway-client)\",\n  \"id\": \"gateway-client\",\n  \"name\": \"openclaw-tui\",\n  \"username\": \"openclaw-tui\"\n}\n```\n\n[Sat 2026-04-11 14:43 GMT+2] When you review AWAA's work, the arc and structural pass is a broader view focusing on the bigger picture, like we discussed.\n1. Pass 1.1 looks at the big ideas, momentum, etc. the arc itself, do the H2 form 3/4 acts of the same story?\n2. Pass 1.2 goes section by section. For each section, is each subsection (H3) contributing something new and unique to its parent H2? List the main ideas in a temporary notepad as you read them and if there are similarities, flag them and send back to AWAA. If a subsection is pointless, flag.\n3. Pass 1.3 goes paragraph by paragraph for each subsection. Does each paragraph support its parent subsection (H3), is it repetition or irrelevant?\n\n4. Pass 2.1 goes section by section. Does each section intro represent the general gist of the section - see the temp notepad\n5. Pass 2.2 goes paragraph by paragraph. Is there a transition between this paragraph and the next?\n6. Pass 2.3 goes paragraph by paragraph. Is there repetition in the paragraph and is every sentence adding value? I often subscribe to the MEAL plan (Main-Idea; Evidence; Analysis; Link/Transition). This does not always apply but it helps.\n\nI need you to codify this as part of your editorial skill - what to do when you get a draft from AWAA. This was triggered by the mess that is paragraph 2 in H3.2.1. Check the original copy and you will see how Pass 2.3 could have addressed this."}],"timestamp":1775911438911}}
{"type":"message","id":"f6697794","parentId":"7d7862e9","timestamp":"2026-04-11T12:44:10.788Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"toolCall","id":"ollama_call_e567d9fe-bb0b-48a5-9ad5-366e06f36cb8","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"iconv -f UTF-16LE -t UTF-8 /home/tiny4lurv/.openclaw/workspace/awaa-output/phase-5-pre-tiny-review.md 2>/dev/null | sed -n '/### The Mechanism: Enforcement Becomes the Evidence of Misclassification/,/### The Chavez-DeRemer/p'"}}],"stopReason":"toolUse","api":"ollama","provider":"ollama","model":"minimax-m2.7:cloud","usage":{"input":80044,"output":146,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":80190,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"timestamp":1775911450787}}
{"type":"message","id":"f12e6b7d","parentId":"f6697794","timestamp":"2026-04-11T12:44:10.839Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"ollama_call_e567d9fe-bb0b-48a5-9ad5-366e06f36cb8","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"### The Mechanism: Enforcement Becomes the Evidence of Misclassification\r\n\r\nCourts determine whether a worker is an employee or an independent contractor by looking at the degree of control the hiring business exercises. The multi-factor test examines behavioral control, financial control, and relationship type. The connection to non-competes is direct. A non-compete clause signals that the hiring business expects to control where the worker can and cannot work. If you are telling a contractor where they cannot work, you are asserting the kind of control that defines an employment relationship. This matters because misclassification carries its own serious consequences that are independent of whatever breach the non-compete was meant to address.\r\n\r\nConsequently, when you send a cease-and-desist or file an injunction over a contractor violation, you are demonstrating to a court that you treated this person as an employee in practice. The enforcement action itself becomes the evidence. Courts do not just read the contract. They examine the relationship behind it. When you enforce the non-compete, the court looks at the full picture of how you managed this worker and finds the control documented in the contract reflected in how you ran the relationship. The logical chain is direct. Enforce the non-compete. The court examines the relationship. Finds excessive control. Reclassifies as employment. Now you owe back wages, benefits, and payroll taxes. You used the clause to protect yourself. The clause is now the exhibit in a case that costs you far more than the original breach would have.\r\n\r\n### The Chavez-DeRemer Case: $9 Million Judgment Where the Non-Compete Was the Exhibit, Not the Primary Liability"}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":0,"durationMs":26,"aggregated":"### The Mechanism: Enforcement Becomes the Evidence of Misclassification\r\n\r\nCourts determine whether a worker is an employee or an independent contractor by looking at the degree of control the hiring business exercises. The multi-factor test examines behavioral control, financial control, and relationship type. The connection to non-competes is direct. A non-compete clause signals that the hiring business expects to control where the worker can and cannot work. If you are telling a contractor where they cannot work, you are asserting the kind of control that defines an employment relationship. This matters because misclassification carries its own serious consequences that are independent of whatever breach the non-compete was meant to address.\r\n\r\nConsequently, when you send a cease-and-desist or file an injunction over a contractor violation, you are demonstrating to a court that you treated this person as an employee in practice. The enforcement action itself becomes the evidence. Courts do not just read the contract. They examine the relationship behind it. When you enforce the non-compete, the court looks at the full picture of how you managed this worker and finds the control documented in the contract reflected in how you ran the relationship. The logical chain is direct. Enforce the non-compete. The court examines the relationship. Finds excessive control. Reclassifies as employment. Now you owe back wages, benefits, and payroll taxes. You used the clause to protect yourself. The clause is now the exhibit in a case that costs you far more than the original breach would have.\r\n\r\n### The Chavez-DeRemer Case: $9 Million Judgment Where the Non-Compete Was the Exhibit, Not the Primary Liability","cwd":"/home/tiny4lurv/.openclaw/workspace"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1775911450829}}
{"type":"message","id":"3a37d501","parentId":"f12e6b7d","timestamp":"2026-04-11T12:44:53.664Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"toolCall","id":"ollama_call_8719434f-7335-432a-a867-8d2d98766e18","name":"edit","arguments":{"path":"/home/tiny4lurv/.openclaw/workspace/skills/editor/SKILL.md","old_string":"## Revision Workflow","new_string":"## AWAA Draft Review Workflow (Codified — Apr 11, 2026)\n\nTriggered by: AWAA Phase 5 output. Run before any readability sweep or line-by-line editing. Each pass narrows focus from big picture to detail.\n\n---\n\n### Phase 1: Arc & Structure (Big Picture)\n\n**Pass 1.1 — Arc Integrity**\n- Does the article tell one story with momentum, or does it feel like a reference doc?\n- Do the H2s form 3-4 acts of the same story, each building on the last?\n- Does the reader's understanding transform from opening to close?\n- If arc is broken → send back to AWAA with arc instructions. Do not proceed.\n\n**Pass 1.2 — Section Audit (H2 by H2)**\n- For each H2 section, list the main ideas of each H3 in a temporary notepad\n- Ask: is each H3 contributing something new and unique to its parent H2?\n- Flag any H3 that overlaps with a sibling H3 in the same or another section\n- Flag any H3 that feels like it has no distinct job\n- If overlaps or redundancies found → send back to AWAA with specific H3s to redirect or cut\n\n**Pass 1.3 — Paragraph Audit (H3 by H3)**\n- For each H3, go paragraph by paragraph\n- Ask: does each paragraph support its parent subsection, or is it repetition/irrelevant?\n- If a paragraph doesn't serve its H3 → flag it\n- Do not fix — flag and return to AWAA if structural\n\n---\n\n### Phase 2: Readability Sweep (My Edit — I Run This)\n\n**Pass 2.1 — Section Intro Audit**\n- Go section by section\n- Does each H2 intro represent the general gist of the section? (Compare against the notepad from Pass 1.2)\n- Is the intro previewing, not parroting? (See Principle 7: intro parroting)\n- If intro misrepresents or parrots → fix the intro\n\n**Pass 2.2 — Transition Audit**\n- Go paragraph by paragraph within each H3\n- Is there a transition between this paragraph and the next?\n- Does the transition signal logical connection, or is it just a mechanical connector word?\n- Fix missing or weak transitions silently\n\n**Pass 2.3 — Sentence-Level Audit (MEAL Plan)**\n- Go paragraph by paragraph\n- Apply MEAL test: **Main idea → Evidence → Analysis → Link/Transition**\n  - **Main**: Does the paragraph have a clear main idea that supports the H3?\n  - **Evidence**: Is there specific evidence (stat, example, mechanism) that supports the main idea?\n  - **Analysis**: Does the paragraph explain *why* the evidence matters, not just what it is?\n  - **Link/Transition**: Does the paragraph end by signaling what the next paragraph will address?\n- Flag repetition within the paragraph — if a sentence merely restates the previous one, cut or redirect\n- Flag paragraphs that announce their logical chain (\"The logical chain is direct: X, Y, Z\") then restate it step by step — this is explainer language, not analysis\n- Flag sentences that exist to fill space rather than add value\n- Fix silently — this is my readability sweep\n\n**The MEAL principle (from Tiny, Apr 11):** \"I often subscribe to the MEAL plan. This does not always apply but it helps.\" MEAL is a diagnostic aid, not a rigid formula. The goal is paragraph coherence — every sentence earns its place by serving the main idea.\n\n---\n\n### How to Keep the Notepad (Pass 1.2)\n\nAs you read each H3, write down its main idea in one line. Keep a running list:\n\n```\nH2.1: What the clause actually restricts\n  H3.1.1: [main idea]\n  H3.1.2: [main idea]\n  H3.1.3: [main idea]\nH2.2: The control contradiction\n  H3.2.1: [main idea]\n  H3.2.2: [main idea]\n  H3.2.3: [main idea]\n```\n\nCompare each H3's main idea against siblings. If two H3s in the same H2 are doing the same job, flag it. If an H3 in H2.1 sounds like one in H2.2, flag it.\n\n---\n\n**Workflow summary:**\n\n| Pass | Scope | Question | Action if fail |\n|------|-------|----------|---------------|\n| 1.1 | Arc | Is this one story with momentum? | Return to AWAA |\n| 1.2 | Section | Is each H3 distinct? | Return to AWAA |\n| 1.3 | H3 | Does each paragraph serve its H3? | Return to AWAA |\n| 2.1 | Intro | Does intro preview vs. parrot? | Fix silently |\n| 2.2 | Transitions | Are paragraphs logically connected? | Fix silently |\n| 2.3 | MEAL | Does every sentence add value? | Fix silently |\n\n**Never skip Phase 1.** If Phase 1 finds problems, do not proceed to Phase 2. Return the draft to AWAA with specific instructions.\n\n---\n\n## Revision Workflow"}}],"stopReason":"toolUse","api":"ollama","provider":"ollama","model":"minimax-m2.7:cloud","usage":{"input":80473,"output":1630,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":82103,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"timestamp":1775911493664}}
{"type":"message","id":"5867e737","parentId":"3a37d501","timestamp":"2026-04-11T12:44:53.744Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"ollama_call_8719434f-7335-432a-a867-8d2d98766e18","toolName":"edit","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Successfully replaced text in /home/tiny4lurv/.openclaw/workspace/skills/editor/SKILL.md."}],"details":{"diff":"     ...\n 341 1. **Suspend-and-Pivot Intro**: Hook the reader with a visceral scene or pain point, pivot to a stat or observation, then introduce the solution.\n 342 2. **Narrative Headers**: Use story-chapter headers like \"The Acquisition Impasse\" — avoid \"Stats Spoilers.\"\n 343 3. **Bridge Protocol**: Use transition words (Furthermore, Consequently, Ultimately, Worse) to connect paragraphs. Avoid \"island\" paragraphs with no logical thread.\n 344 \n+345 ## AWAA Draft Review Workflow (Codified — Apr 11, 2026)\n+346 \n+347 Triggered by: AWAA Phase 5 output. Run before any readability sweep or line-by-line editing. Each pass narrows focus from big picture to detail.\n+348 \n+349 ---\n+350 \n+351 ### Phase 1: Arc & Structure (Big Picture)\n+352 \n+353 **Pass 1.1 — Arc Integrity**\n+354 - Does the article tell one story with momentum, or does it feel like a reference doc?\n+355 - Do the H2s form 3-4 acts of the same story, each building on the last?\n+356 - Does the reader's understanding transform from opening to close?\n+357 - If arc is broken → send back to AWAA with arc instructions. Do not proceed.\n+358 \n+359 **Pass 1.2 — Section Audit (H2 by H2)**\n+360 - For each H2 section, list the main ideas of each H3 in a temporary notepad\n+361 - Ask: is each H3 contributing something new and unique to its parent H2?\n+362 - Flag any H3 that overlaps with a sibling H3 in the same or another section\n+363 - Flag any H3 that feels like it has no distinct job\n+364 - If overlaps or redundancies found → send back to AWAA with specific H3s to redirect or cut\n+365 \n+366 **Pass 1.3 — Paragraph Audit (H3 by H3)**\n+367 - For each H3, go paragraph by paragraph\n+368 - Ask: does each paragraph support its parent subsection, or is it repetition/irrelevant?\n+369 - If a paragraph doesn't serve its H3 → flag it\n+370 - Do not fix — flag and return to AWAA if structural\n+371 \n+372 ---\n+373 \n+374 ### Phase 2: Readability Sweep (My Edit — I Run This)\n+375 \n+376 **Pass 2.1 — Section Intro Audit**\n+377 - Go section by section\n+378 - Does each H2 intro represent the general gist of the section? (Compare against the notepad from Pass 1.2)\n+379 - Is the intro previewing, not parroting? (See Principle 7: intro parroting)\n+380 - If intro misrepresents or parrots → fix the intro\n+381 \n+382 **Pass 2.2 — Transition Audit**\n+383 - Go paragraph by paragraph within each H3\n+384 - Is there a transition between this paragraph and the next?\n+385 - Does the transition signal logical connection, or is it just a mechanical connector word?\n+386 - Fix missing or weak transitions silently\n+387 \n+388 **Pass 2.3 — Sentence-Level Audit (MEAL Plan)**\n+389 - Go paragraph by paragraph\n+390 - Apply MEAL test: **Main idea → Evidence → Analysis → Link/Transition**\n+391   - **Main**: Does the paragraph have a clear main idea that supports the H3?\n+392   - **Evidence**: Is there specific evidence (stat, example, mechanism) that supports the main idea?\n+393   - **Analysis**: Does the paragraph explain *why* the evidence matters, not just what it is?\n+394   - **Link/Transition**: Does the paragraph end by signaling what the next paragraph will address?\n+395 - Flag repetition within the paragraph — if a sentence merely restates the previous one, cut or redirect\n+396 - Flag paragraphs that announce their logical chain (\"The logical chain is direct: X, Y, Z\") then restate it step by step — this is explainer language, not analysis\n+397 - Flag sentences that exist to fill space rather than add value\n+398 - Fix silently — this is my readability sweep\n+399 \n+400 **The MEAL principle (from Tiny, Apr 11):** \"I often subscribe to the MEAL plan. This does not always apply but it helps.\" MEAL is a diagnostic aid, not a rigid formula. The goal is paragraph coherence — every sentence earns its place by serving the main idea.\n+401 \n+402 ---\n+403 \n+404 ### How to Keep the Notepad (Pass 1.2)\n+405 \n+406 As you read each H3, write down its main idea in one line. Keep a running list:\n+407 \n+408 ```\n+409 H2.1: What the clause actually restricts\n+410   H3.1.1: [main idea]\n+411   H3.1.2: [main idea]\n+412   H3.1.3: [main idea]\n+413 H2.2: The control contradiction\n+414   H3.2.1: [main idea]\n+415   H3.2.2: [main idea]\n+416   H3.2.3: [main idea]\n+417 ```\n+418 \n+419 Compare each H3's main idea against siblings. If two H3s in the same H2 are doing the same job, flag it. If an H3 in H2.1 sounds like one in H2.2, flag it.\n+420 \n+421 ---\n+422 \n+423 **Workflow summary:**\n+424 \n+425 | Pass | Scope | Question | Action if fail |\n+426 |------|-------|----------|---------------|\n+427 | 1.1 | Arc | Is this one story with momentum? | Return to AWAA |\n+428 | 1.2 | Section | Is each H3 distinct? | Return to AWAA |\n+429 | 1.3 | H3 | Does each paragraph serve its H3? | Return to AWAA |\n+430 | 2.1 | Intro | Does intro preview vs. parrot? | Fix silently |\n+431 | 2.2 | Transitions | Are paragraphs logically connected? | Fix silently |\n+432 | 2.3 | MEAL | Does every sentence add value? | Fix silently |\n+433 \n+434 **Never skip Phase 1.** If Phase 1 finds problems, do not proceed to Phase 2. Return the draft to AWAA with specific instructions.\n+435 \n+436 ---\n+437 \n 345 ## Revision Workflow\n 346 \n 347 ### Pass 1: Structure Audit\n 348 - [ ] All H2 sections have contextualizing intros\n     ...","firstChangedLine":345},"isError":false,"timestamp":1775911493728}}
{"type":"message","id":"6f2445df","parentId":"5867e737","timestamp":"2026-04-11T12:45:10.273Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Now let me show you what Pass 2.3 would have caught in H3.2.1 P2:\n\nThe paragraph reads:\n> \"Consequently, when you send a cease-and-desist or file an injunction over a contractor violation, you are demonstrating to a court that you treated this person as an employee in practice. The enforcement action itself becomes the evidence. Courts do not just read the contract. They examine the relationship behind it. When you enforce the non-compete, the court looks at the full picture of how you managed this worker and finds the control documented in the contract reflected in how you ran the relationship. The logical chain is direct. Enforce the non-compete. The court examines the relationship. Finds excessive control. Reclassifies as employment. Now you owe back wages, benefits, and payroll taxes. You used the clause to protect yourself. The clause is now the exhibit in a case that costs you far more than the original breach would have.\"\n\nPass 2.3 MEAL check:\n\n- **Main**: \"Enforcing a non-compete creates misclassification evidence\" — clear main idea. ✅\n- **Evidence**: The step-by-step chain (\"Enforce → examine → find control → reclassify\") — this is the evidence. ✅\n- **Analysis**: Missing. The paragraph walks through the mechanism but never explains *why* this chain leads to back wages and payroll taxes. It states consequences without analysis.\n- **Link/Transition**: The paragraph ends by stating the consequence, not by signaling what the next paragraph (Chavez-DeRemer) will add.\n\nThe real problem: \"The logical chain is direct. Enforce the non-compete. The court examines the relationship. Finds excessive control. Reclassifies as employment.\" — this is explainer language. It's announcing the logic rather than demonstrating it. A MEAL-compliant paragraph would show *how* reclassification produces back wages, not list the steps like a legal flowchart.\n\nThat phrase — \"The logical chain is direct\" — is a signal that AWAA is narrating the mechanism instead of proving it. It should have been flagged in Pass 2.3.\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"ollama_call_404e4bc3-9d64-4a38-a2d7-6e9a68eddc4d","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"cd /home/tiny4lurv/.openclaw/workspace && git add -A && git commit -m \"editor-skill: AWAA draft review workflow codified - Pass 1.1 to 2.3, MEAL plan\""}}],"stopReason":"toolUse","api":"ollama","provider":"ollama","model":"minimax-m2.7:cloud","usage":{"input":81689,"output":545,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":82234,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"timestamp":1775911510266}}
{"type":"message","id":"e8a2ab19","parentId":"6f2445df","timestamp":"2026-04-11T12:45:10.795Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"ollama_call_404e4bc3-9d64-4a38-a2d7-6e9a68eddc4d","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"[master c1a3975] editor-skill: AWAA draft review workflow codified - Pass 1.1 to 2.3, MEAL plan\n 1 file changed, 93 insertions(+)"}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":0,"durationMs":469,"aggregated":"[master c1a3975] editor-skill: AWAA draft review workflow codified - Pass 1.1 to 2.3, MEAL plan\n 1 file changed, 93 insertions(+)","cwd":"/home/tiny4lurv/.openclaw/workspace"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1775911510774}}
{"type":"message","id":"d3af805f","parentId":"e8a2ab19","timestamp":"2026-04-11T12:45:27.293Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"toolCall","id":"ollama_call_0d51dba0-9c91-4f8d-82d6-d8bab1b28f8f","name":"edit","arguments":{"new_string":"## AWAA Draft Review Workflow — Codified (14:43 UTC)\n\nTiny provided explicit 6-pass structure for AWAA draft review. Codified in editor-skill.\n\n**Phase 1 (Arc & Structure — return to AWAA if failures):**\n- Pass 1.1: Arc integrity — do H2s form 3-4 acts of one story?\n- Pass 1.2: Section audit — temp notepad of H3 main ideas, flag overlaps/similarities\n- Pass 1.3: Paragraph audit — does each paragraph support its H3?\n\n**Phase 2 (Readability Sweep — fix silently):**\n- Pass 2.1: Section intro audit — preview vs. parroting check\n- Pass 2.2: Transition audit — paragraph-to-paragraph logical connections\n- Pass 2.3: MEAL plan — Main/Idea Evidence/Analysis/Link. Flag explainer language (\"the logical chain is direct\"), list-step consequences, sentences that merely restate\n\n**MEAL caveat (Ty's)**: \"This does not always apply but it helps.\" MEAL is a diagnostic aid, not a rigid formula.\n\n**Paragraph 2 of H3.2.1 failed Pass 2.3**: \"The logical chain is direct. Enforce → examine → find → reclassify\" is explainer language announcing the mechanism rather than demonstrating it. Never state \"the logical chain is direct\" — show it through analysis instead.\n\n**Key failure caught by Pass 2.3**: The \"logical chain\" sentence in H3.2.1 P2 — AWAA narrating the mechanism like a flowchart instead of analyzing it.\n\n**Workflow rule:** Never skip Phase 1. If Phase 1 finds problems → return to AWAA before Phase 2.\n\n---\n\n## Pending Work","old_string":"## Pending Work","path":"/home/tiny4lurv/.openclaw/workspace/memory/2026-04-11.md"}}],"stopReason":"toolUse","api":"ollama","provider":"ollama","model":"minimax-m2.7:cloud","usage":{"input":82254,"output":479,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":82733,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"timestamp":1775911527292}}
{"type":"message","id":"cd3bb06a","parentId":"d3af805f","timestamp":"2026-04-11T12:45:27.356Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"ollama_call_0d51dba0-9c91-4f8d-82d6-d8bab1b28f8f","toolName":"edit","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Successfully replaced text in /home/tiny4lurv/.openclaw/workspace/memory/2026-04-11.md."}],"details":{"diff":"     ...\n 253 **Rule added:** \"When you make a mistake: acknowledge it, explain how it might have happened, stop there. Do not propose a fix, do not describe what you will do differently, do not offer a solution. Tiny will tell you if he wants a fix. If he asks 'how did you miss this?' he wants the diagnostic, not the prescription.\"\n 254 \n 255 ---\n 256 \n+257 ## AWAA Draft Review Workflow — Codified (14:43 UTC)\n+258 \n+259 Tiny provided explicit 6-pass structure for AWAA draft review. Codified in editor-skill.\n+260 \n+261 **Phase 1 (Arc & Structure — return to AWAA if failures):**\n+262 - Pass 1.1: Arc integrity — do H2s form 3-4 acts of one story?\n+263 - Pass 1.2: Section audit — temp notepad of H3 main ideas, flag overlaps/similarities\n+264 - Pass 1.3: Paragraph audit — does each paragraph support its H3?\n+265 \n+266 **Phase 2 (Readability Sweep — fix silently):**\n+267 - Pass 2.1: Section intro audit — preview vs. parroting check\n+268 - Pass 2.2: Transition audit — paragraph-to-paragraph logical connections\n+269 - Pass 2.3: MEAL plan — Main/Idea Evidence/Analysis/Link. Flag explainer language (\"the logical chain is direct\"), list-step consequences, sentences that merely restate\n+270 \n+271 **MEAL caveat (Ty's)**: \"This does not always apply but it helps.\" MEAL is a diagnostic aid, not a rigid formula.\n+272 \n+273 **Paragraph 2 of H3.2.1 failed Pass 2.3**: \"The logical chain is direct. Enforce → examine → find → reclassify\" is explainer language announcing the mechanism rather than demonstrating it. Never state \"the logical chain is direct\" — show it through analysis instead.\n+274 \n+275 **Key failure caught by Pass 2.3**: The \"logical chain\" sentence in H3.2.1 P2 — AWAA narrating the mechanism like a flowchart instead of analyzing it.\n+276 \n+277 **Workflow rule:** Never skip Phase 1. If Phase 1 finds problems → return to AWAA before Phase 2.\n+278 \n+279 ---\n+280 \n 257 ## Pending Work\n 258 \n 259 | Item | Status |\n 260 |------|--------|\n     ...","firstChangedLine":257},"isError":false,"timestamp":1775911527341}}
